# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ayam-kampong
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] The **Ayam Kampong** (older spelling) or **Ayam Kampung** is a chicken breed from Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] The name means simply "free-range chicken" or literally "village chicken".
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] In Indonesia and Malaysia, the term *ayam kampung* refer to indigenous chickens that are raised using traditional free range production techniques by almost every household in the village.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] It is a diverse population which resulted from the uncontrolled cross-breeding of red jungle-fowl, indigenous Southeast Asian chickens and exotic chickens of various types imported in the late 1800s by European, mainly Dutch and British, settlers.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] The Ayam Kampong is a small dual-purpose chicken.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] They are slow-growing breed that contributed to its low productivity.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] Both its physical characteristics and its colouring are highly variable.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] Three principal colour types are recognised.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] The commonest is the black-red variety, in which cocks are mainly green-black with glossy red-brown back, neck hackles and saddle feathers.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] Other varieties are the red type and the naked-neck type.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] Traditionally Ayam Kampong have been raised by most of the rural population of Indonesia and they represent an important source of meat and eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] However, due to their low production, Ayam Kampong are not able to provide consumption on a daily basis.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] Nevertheless, they are traditionally consumed on most family occasions and celebrations.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] Ayam Kampong hens left to forage lay about 55 or 100 brown eggs per year, with an average weight of 39 g.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] The poor performance as an egg producer is attributed to the broodiness of the hens.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] In meat production, birds reach a market weight of 1–1.5 kg in three or four months.
[src:ayam-kampong/ayam-kampong] The meat commands a higher price than that of commercial breeds.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] A **broiler** is any chicken (*Gallus gallus domesticus*) bred and raised specifically for meat production.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Most commercial broilers reach slaughter weight between four and six weeks of age, although slower growing breeds reach slaughter weight at approximately 14 weeks of age.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Average broilers have white feathers and yellowish skin.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Broiler or, less commonly, **broiler-fryer** is also used sometimes to refer specifically to younger chickens under 2.0 kilograms (4+1⁄2 lb), as compared with the larger roasters.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Due to extensive breeding selection for rapid early growth and the husbandry used to sustain this, broilers are susceptible to several welfare concerns, particularly skeletal malformation and dysfunction, skin and eye lesions and congestive heart conditions.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Management of ventilation, housing, stocking density and in-house procedures must be evaluated regularly to support good welfare of the flock.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The breeding stock (broiler-breeders) do grow to maturity but also have their own welfare concerns related to the frustration of a high feeding motivation and beak trimming.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Broilers are usually grown as mixed-sex flocks in large sheds under intensive conditions.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Before the development of modern commercial meat breeds, broilers were mostly young male chickens culled from farm flocks.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Magazines for the poultry industry existed at this time.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] A crossbred variety of chicken was produced from a male of a naturally double-breasted Cornish strain, and a female of a tall, large-boned strain of white Plymouth Rocks.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] This first attempt at a meat crossbreed was introduced in the 1930s and became dominant in the 1960s.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The original crossbreed was plagued by problems of low fertility, slow growth and disease susceptibility.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Modern broilers have become very different from the Cornish/Rock crossbreeds.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] As an example, Donald Shaver (originally a breeder of egg-production breeds) began gathering breeding stock for a broiler program in 1950.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Besides the breeds normally favored, Cornish Game, Plymouth Rock, New Hampshire, Langshans, Jersey Black Giant, and Brahmas were included.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] A white feathered female line was purchased from Cobb.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] A full-scale breeding program was commenced in 1958, with commercial shipments in Canada and the US in 1959 and in Europe in 1963.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] As a second example, color sexing broilers was proposed by Shaver in 1973.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The genetics were based on the company's breeding plan for egg layers, which had been developed in the mid-1960s.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] A difficulty facing the breeders of the color-sexed broiler is that the chicken must be white-feathered by slaughter age.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] After 12 years, accurate color sexing without compromising economic traits was achieved.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Artificial insemination is a mechanism in which spermatozoa are deposited into the reproductive tract of a female.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Artificial insemination provides a number of benefits relating to reproduction in the poultry industry.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Broiler breeds have been selected specifically for growth, causing them to develop large pectoral muscles, which interfere with and reduce natural mating.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The amount of sperm produced and deposited in the hen's reproductive tract may be limited because of this.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Additionally, the males' overall sex drive may be significantly reduced due to growth selection.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Artificial insemination has allowed many farmers to incorporate selected genes into their stock, increasing their genetic quality.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Abdominal massage is the most common method used for semen collection.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] During this process, the rooster is restrained and the back region located towards the tail and behind the wings is caressed.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Within a short period of time, the male should get an erection of the phallus.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Once this occurs, the cloaca is squeezed and semen is collected from the external papilla of the vas deferens.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] During artificial insemination, semen is most frequently deposited intra-vaginally by means of a plastic syringe.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] In order for semen to be deposited here, the vaginal orifice is everted through the cloaca.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] This is simply done by applying pressure to the abdomen of the hen.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The semen-containing instrument is placed 2–4 cm into the vaginal orifice.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] As the semen is deposited, the pressure applied to the hen's abdomen is released simultaneously.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The person performing this procedure typically uses one hand to move and direct the tail feathers, while using the other hand to insert the instrument and semen into the vagina.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Modern commercial broilers, for example, Cornish crosses and Cornish-Rocks, are artificially selected and bred for large-scale, efficient meat production.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] They are noted for having very fast growth rates, a high feed conversion ratio, and low levels of activity.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Modern commercial broilers are bred to reach a slaughter-weight of about 2 kg (4.4 lb) in only 5 to 7 weeks.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] As a consequence, the behaviour and physiology of broilers reared for meat are those of immature birds, rather than adults.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Slow growing free-range and organic strains have been developed which reach slaughter-weight at 12 to 16 weeks of age.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Typical broilers have white feathers and yellowish skin.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Recent genetic analysis has revealed that the gene for yellow skin was incorporated into domestic birds through hybridization with the grey junglefowl (*G. sonneratii*).
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Modern crosses are also favorable for meat production because they lack the typical "hair" which many breeds have that must be removed by singeing after plucking the carcass.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Both male and female broilers are reared for their meat.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Broiler behavior is modified by the environment, and alters as the broilers' age and bodyweight rapidly increase.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] For example, the activity of broilers reared outdoors is initially greater than broilers reared indoors, but from six weeks of age, decreases to comparable levels in all groups.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The same study shows that in the outdoors group, surprisingly little use is made of the extra space and facilities such as perches – it was proposed that the main reason for this was leg weakness as 80 per cent of the birds had a detectable gait abnormality at seven weeks of age.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] There is no evidence of reduced motivation to extend the behavioral repertoire, as, for example, ground pecking remained at significantly higher levels in the outdoor groups because this behavior could also be performed from a lying posture rather than standing.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Examining the frequency of all sexual behaviour shows a large decrease with age, suggestive of a decline in libido.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The decline in libido is not enough to account for reduced fertility in heavy cocks at 58 weeks and is probably a consequence of the large bulk or the conformation of the males at this age interfering in some way with the transfer of semen during copulations which otherwise look normal.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Chickens are omnivores and modern broilers are given access to a special diet of high protein feed, usually delivered via an automated feeding system.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] This is combined with artificial lighting conditions to stimulate eating and growth and thus the desired body weight.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] In the U.S., the average feed conversion ratio (FCR) of a broiler was 1.91 kilograms of feed per kilograms of liveweight in 2011, an improvement from 4.70 in 1925.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] New Zealand commercial broiler farms have recorded the world's best broiler chicken FCR at 1.38.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The microbiome of the broiler also has a large effect in addition to the birds nutrition and genetics on overall FCR.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Artificial selection has led to a great increase in the pace of which broilers develop and reach slaughter-weight.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Selection and husbandry for very fast growth means there is a genetically induced mismatch between the energy-supplying organs of the broiler and its energy-consuming organs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] This genetic selection for very fast growth at the cost of welfare has led animal welfare campaigners to describe the most commonly used broiler breeds as Frankenchickens.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Rapid growth can lead to metabolic disorders such as sudden death syndrome by acute heart failure, killing up to 3% in Europe, and ascites, a slower form of hearth failure that affect an additional 5% worldwide.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Breeding for increased breast muscle affects the way chickens walk and puts additional stress on their hips and legs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] There is a high frequency of skeletal problems in broilers, mainly in the locomotory system.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] These leg abnormalities impair the locomotor abilities of the birds, and lame birds spend more time lying and sleeping.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Increased inactivity is linked with an increase in dermatitis caused by a greater amount of time in contact with ammonia in poultry litter.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Broilers are usually kept at high stocking densities.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Management conditions (litter quality, temperature and humidity) are however more important than stocking density.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Many broilers die during the processes of catching, packing and transport.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The commercial production of broiler chickens for meat consumption is a highly industrialized process.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] There are two major sectors: (1) rearing birds intended for consumption and (2) rearing parent stock for breeding the meat birds.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] A report in 2005 stated that around 5.9 billion broiler chickens for eating were produced yearly in the European Union.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Mass production of chicken meat is a global industry and at that time, only two or three breeding companies supplied around 90% of the world's breeder-broilers.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] The total number of meat chickens produced in the world was nearly 47 billion in 2004; of these, approximately 19% were produced in the US, 15% in China, 13% in the EU25 and 11% in Brazil.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Consumption of broilers is surpassing that of beef in industrialized countries, with demand rising in Asia.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Worldwide, 86.6 million tonnes of broiler meat were produced in 2014, and as of 2018, the worldwide estimation of broiler chick population was approximately 23 billion.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] It is believed that the thermal comfort zone for poultry is in the 18–25 °C (64–77 °F) range.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Some papers describe 26–35 °C (79–95 °F) as the "critical zone" for heat stress, but others report that due to acclimatization, birds in the tropical countries do not begin to experience heat stress until 32 °C (90 °F).
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] There is wider agreement that temperatures greater than 35 °C (95 °F) and 47 °C (117 °F) form "upper critical" and lethal zones, respectively.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Average daily temperatures of around 33 °C (91 °F) are known to interfere with feeding in both broilers and egg hens, as well as lower their immune response, with outcomes such as reduced weight gain/egg production or greater incidence of salmonella infections, footpad dermatitis or meningitis.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Persistent heat stress leads to oxidative stress in tissues, and harvested white meat ends up with a lower proportion of essential compounds like vitamin E, lutein and zeaxanthin, yet an increase in glucose and cholesterol.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Multiple studies show that dietary supplementation with chromium can help to relieve these issues due to its antioxidative properties, particularly in combination with zinc or herbs like wood sorrel.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Resveratrol is another popular antioxidant administered to poultry for these reasons.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Though the effect of supplementation is limited, it is much cheaper than interventions to improve cooling or simply stock fewer birds, and so remains popular.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] Around 2003, it was estimated that the poultry industry in the United States already lost up to $165 million annually due to heat stress at the time.
[src:ayam-kampong/broiler] On the contrary, if the warming is kept to 1.5 °C (2.7 °F), costs at moderately modernized farms increase the least, by 12.5%, followed by the most modernized farms with a 19.9% increase, and the least technological farms seeing the greatest increase.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] In wild birds, egg incubation is a normal and essential phase in the process of reproduction, and in many families of birds, e.g. pigeons, the eggs are incubated by both male and female parents.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] In all species of phalaropes, the males become broody rather than the female.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The females leave the nest after finishing laying to let the males incubate the eggs and take care of the young.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Male emus (*Dromaius novaehollandiae*) become broody after their mates start laying, and begin to incubate the eggs before the laying period is complete.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Male cassowaries are the ones who brood and raise the chicks, with the females playing no role beyond laying the eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] A small number of atypical birds such as *Passeriformes* of the genus *Molothrus* (cowbirds) do not become broody but lay their eggs in the nests of other species for incubation, known as brood parasitism.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The Australian brushturkey *(Alectura lathami)* also does not become broody, rather, it covers the eggs with a large mound of vegetable matter, which decomposes, keeping the eggs warm until hatching.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The crab-plover (*Dromas ardeola*), which lives on the coasts and islands of the Indian Ocean, lets its eggs incubate primarily by the heat of the sun, and will leave its nest unattended, occasionally for days at a time.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Broody hens can be recognized by their behaviour.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] They sit firmly over the eggs, and when people approach or try to remove the eggs, they threaten the person by erecting their feathers, emitting a characteristic sound like *clo-clo-clo* and will peck aggressively.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] When broody, hens often temporarily cease eating or reduce their feed consumption.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Letting eggs accumulate in a relatively dark place near the floor often stimulates hens to become broody.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Placing artificial eggs into nests also stimulates broodiness.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Keeping hens in dark places with warm temperatures and in view of vocalising orphan chicks can induce broodiness, even in breeds that normally do not go broody.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Some environmental conditions stimulate broodiness.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] In heavy breeds of chickens, warm weather tends to bring about broodiness.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Removing eggs each day, out of the sight of the hens, helps avoid broodiness not only in domestic poultry but also in some wild species in captivity.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] This continued egg laying means more eggs are laid than would occur under natural conditions.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Poultry farming in battery cages also helps to avoid broodiness.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Because hens stop laying when they become broody, commercial poultry breeders perceive broodiness as an impediment to egg and poultry meat production.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] With domestication, it has become more profitable to incubate eggs artificially, while keeping hens in full egg production.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] To help achieve this, there has been intense artificial selection for non-broodiness in commercial egg laying chickens and parent stock of poultry.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] As a result of this artificial selection, broodiness has been reduced to very low levels in present-day breeds of commercial fowl, both among egg-laying and meat-producing breeds.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Broodiness is due to the secretion of the hormone prolactin by the anterior lobe of the hypophysis.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Prolactin injection in hens provokes egg laying to stop within a few days, vitellum reabsorption, ovary regression (hens only have a left ovary) and finally broodiness.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] However, attempts to stop broodiness by the administration of several hormones have failed because this state, once evoked, requires time to revert.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Prolactin injections inhibit the production of gonadotropin hormone, a hormone that stimulates ovarian follicles which is produced in the frontal lobe of hypophysis.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Castrated males can go broody with baby chicks, showing that broodiness is not limited to females, however, castrated males do not incubate eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Contrary to common opinion, the temperature of broody hens barely differs from that of laying hens.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Broody hens pluck feathers from their chest, using them to cover the eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] As a consequence of this, they develop one or several patches of bare skin on the ventral surface.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] These reddish, well-vascularized areas of skin are usually called brood patches which improve heat transfer to the eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Broodiness is more common in some chicken breeds than others, indicating that it is a heritable characteristic.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Breeds such as Cochin, Cornish and Silkie exhibit a tendency to broodiness, including brooding eggs from other species such as quails, pheasants, turkeys and geese.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] In some breeds such as the White Leghorn, broodiness is extremely rare.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Some studies on crosses of chicken breeds point to the hypothesis of complementary genes acting on broodiness.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Other results point to the hypothesis of sex-linked genes, or, inheritance through the maternal chromosome.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Although these studies have been made on different breeds of chickens, their results are not contradictory.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] There is common agreement that artificial selection for egg production succeeded in reducing the incidence of broody hens in chicken populations.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] There is some evidence that non-avian dinosaurs also practiced brooding.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] A specimen of the extinct Mongolian oviraptorid *Citipati osmolskae* was discovered in a chicken-like brooding position in 1993, which may indicate that they had begun using an insulating layer of feathers to keep the eggs warm.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Several deinonychosaur and oviraptorosaur specimens have also been found preserved on top of their nests, likely brooding in a bird-like manner.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Lungless salamanders in the family *Plethodontidae* lay a small number of eggs in a cluster among damp leaf litter.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The female salamander often broods the eggs and in the genus *Ensatinas*, she has been observed to coil around them and press her throat area against them, effectively massaging them with a mucous secretion.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The black mountain salamander mother broods her eggs, guarding them from predation as the larvae feed on the yolks of their eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] They eventually break their way out of the egg capsules and disperse.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Some species of Gymnophiona (caecilians, with long, cylindrical, limbless bodies) brood their eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Most pythons coil around their egg-clutches and remain with them until they hatch.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] A female python will not leave the eggs, except to occasionally bask in the sun or drink water.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] She will even “shiver” to generate heat to incubate the eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Some cichlid fish lay their eggs in the open, on rocks, leaves, or logs.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Male and female parents usually engage in differing brooding roles.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Most commonly, the male patrols the pair's territory and repels intruders, while females fan water over the eggs, removing the infertile and leading the fry while foraging.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] However, both sexes are able to perform the full range of parenting behaviours.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Mouthbrooding, also known as oral incubation, refers to the care given by some groups of animals to fertilized eggs or their offspring by holding them in the mouth of the parent for extended periods of time.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Although it has been observed in a variety of animals, most mouthbrooders are fish.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The parent performing this behavior invariably feeds less often and afterwards will be underweight, requiring a period of feeding and restoring the depleted energy reserves.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Marsupial frogs are so-called broody because they possess a dorsal brood pouch.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] In some species the eggs are fertilized on the female's lower back, and are inserted in her pouch with the aid of the male's toes.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The eggs remain in contact with the female's vascular tissue, which provides them oxygen.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] Some animals have a common name that includes the word 'brood' or its derivatives, although it is arguable whether the animals show 'broodiness' per se.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] For example, the female gastric-brooding frog (*Rheobatrachus sp.*) from Australia, now probably extinct, swallows her fertilized eggs, which then develop inside her stomach.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] She ceases to feed and stops secreting stomach acid and the tadpoles rely on the yolks of the eggs for nourishment.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] After six or seven weeks the mother opens her mouth wide and regurgitates the tadpoles which hop away from her mouth.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The brooding sea anemone (*Epiactis prolifera*) is a colonial hermaphrodite that fertilizes and incubates its eggs internally.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The motile larvae, after swimming out of the mouth, migrate down to the disk and become fixed there until they become little anemones, ready to move and feed independently.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] In Darwin's frog (*Rhinoderma darwinii*), the female lays about 30 eggs and then the male guards them for about two weeks, until they hatch.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] The male then takes all the survivors and carries around the developing young in his vocal pouch.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] When the tiny tadpoles have developed they hop out and swim away.
[src:ayam-kampong/broodiness] In this animal, the parents hold the hatched young rather than eggs in their mouths, so is arguably not showing 'broodiness'.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The **chicken** (***Gallus gallus domesticus***) is the domesticated form of the red junglefowl (*Gallus gallus*), originally native to Southeast Asia.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] It was first domesticated around 8,000 years ago and is one of the most common and widespread domesticated animals in the world.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are primarily kept for their meat and eggs, though they are also kept as pets.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] As of 2023, the global chicken population exceeds 26.5 billion, with more than 50 billion birds produced annually for consumption.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Specialized breeds such as broilers and laying hens have been developed for meat and egg production, respectively.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] A hen bred for laying can produce over 300 eggs per year.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are social animals with complex vocalizations and behaviors, and feature in folklore, religion, and literature across many societies.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Their economic importance makes them a central component of global animal husbandry.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The word *chicken* comes from Old English *cicen* (pronounced essentially the same as in Modern English).
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] While the origin is Germanic, it is unclear exactly where the word came from, although it could ultimately have come from an imitation of the sound a chicken makes.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are relatively large birds, active by day.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The body is round, the legs are unfeathered in most breeds, and the wings are short.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Wild junglefowl can fly, whereas domestic chickens and their flight muscles are too heavy to allow them to fly more than a short distance.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Size and coloration vary widely between breeds.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Newly hatched chicks of both modern and heritage varieties weigh the same, about 37 g (1.3 oz).
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Modern varieties however grow much faster; by day 35 a Ross 708 broiler may weigh 1.8 kg (4.0 lb) as against the 1.05 kg (2.3 lb) of a heritage chicken of the same age.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Adult chickens of both sexes have a fleshy crest on their heads called a comb or cockscomb, and hanging flaps of skin on either side under their beaks called wattles; combs and wattles are more prominent in males.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Some breeds have a mutation that causes extra feathering under the face, giving the appearance of a beard.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In the wild, they scratch at the soil to search for seeds, insects, and animals as large as lizards, small snakes, and young mice.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] A chicken may live for 5–10 years, depending on the breed.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The world's oldest known chicken lived for 16 years.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are gregarious, living in flocks, and incubate eggs and raise young communally.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Individual chickens dominate others, establishing a pecking order; dominant individuals take priority for access to food and nest sites.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The concept of dominance, involving pecking, was described in female chickens by Thorleif Schjelderup-Ebbe in 1921 as the "pecking order".
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Male chickens tend to leap and use their claws in conflicts.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are capable of mobbing and killing a weak or inexperienced predator, such as a young fox.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens have been thought of primarily as providers of food, but their cognition, emotions, and sociality are comparable with other birds and mammals.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] A male's crowing is a loud and sometimes shrill call, serving as a territorial signal to other males, and in response to sudden disturbances within their surroundings.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Hens cluck loudly after laying an egg and to call their chicks.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens give different warning calls to indicate that a predator is approaching from the air or on the ground.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] To initiate courting, some roosters may dance in a circle around or near a hen (a circle dance), often lowering the wing which is closest to the hen.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The dance triggers a response in the hen and when she responds to his call, the rooster may mount the hen and proceed with the mating.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Mating typically involves a sequence in which the male approaches the female and performs a waltzing display.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] If the female is unreceptive, she runs off; otherwise, she crouches, and the male mounts, treading with both feet on her back.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] After copulation the male does a tail-bending display.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Sperm transfer occurs by cloacal contact between the male and female, in an action called the 'cloacal kiss'.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] As with all birds, reproduction is controlled by a neuroendocrine system, the Gonadotropin-Releasing Hormone-I neurons in the hypothalamus.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Reproductive hormones including estrogen, progesterone, and gonadotropins (luteinizing hormone and follicle-stimulating hormone) initiate and maintain sexual maturation changes.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Reproduction declines with age, thought to be due to a decline in GnRH-I-N.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Hens often try to lay in nests that already contain eggs and sometimes move eggs from neighbouring nests into their own.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] A flock thus uses only a few preferred locations, rather than having a different nest for every bird.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Under natural conditions, most birds lay only until a clutch is complete; they then incubate all the eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The hen sits on the nest, fluffing up or pecking defensively if disturbed.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] She rarely leaves the nest until the eggs have hatched.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Eggs of chickens from the high-altitude region of Tibet have special physiological adaptations that result in a higher hatching rate in low oxygen environments.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] When eggs are placed in a hypoxic environment, chicken embryos from these populations express much more hemoglobin than embryos from other chicken populations.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] This hemoglobin has a greater affinity for oxygen, binding oxygen more readily.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Fertile chicken eggs hatch at the end of the incubation period, about 21 days; the chick uses its egg tooth to break out of the shell.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Hens remain on the nest for about two days after the first chick hatches; during this time the newly hatched chicks feed by absorbing the internal yolk sac.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The hen guards her chicks and broods them to keep them warm.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] She leads them to food and water and calls them towards food.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The chicks imprint on the hen and subsequently follow her continually.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] She continues to care for them until they are several weeks old.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Inbreeding of White Leghorn chickens tends to cause inbreeding depression expressed as reduced egg number and delayed sexual maturity.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Strongly inbred Langshan chickens display obvious inbreeding depression in reproduction, particularly for traits such as age when the first egg is laid and egg number.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Water or ground-dwelling fowl similar to modern partridges, in the Galliformes, the order of bird to which chickens belong, survived the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event that killed all tree-dwelling birds and their dinosaur relatives.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are descended primarily from the red junglefowl (*Gallus gallus*) and are scientifically classified as the same species.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Domesticated chickens freely interbreed with populations of red junglefowl.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The domestic chicken has subsequently hybridised with grey junglefowl, Sri Lankan junglefowl and green junglefowl; a gene for yellow skin, for instance, was incorporated into domestic birds from the grey junglefowl (*G. sonneratii*).
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] It is estimated that chickens share between 71 and 79% of their genome with red junglefowl.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The red junglefowl is well adapted to take advantage of the vast quantities of seed produced during the end of the multi-decade bamboo seeding cycle, to boost its own reproduction.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In domesticating the chicken, humans took advantage of the red junglefowl's ability to reproduce prolifically when exposed to a surge in its food supply.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Exactly when and where the chicken was domesticated was controversial.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Genomic studies estimated that the chicken was domesticated 8,000 years ago in Southeast Asia and spread to China and India 2,000 to 3,000 years later.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Archaeological evidence appeared to support domestic chickens in Southeast Asia well before 6000 BC, China by 6000 BC and India by 2000 BC.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] An early study proposed that a single domestication event of the red junglefowl in present-day Thailand gave rise to the modern chicken.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] A 2020 *Nature* study that fully sequenced 863 chickens across the world suggests that all domestic chickens originate from a single domestication event of red junglefowl (*Gallus gallus*) whose present-day distribution is predominantly in Southeast Asia.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] These domesticated chickens spread across Southeast and South Asia where they interbred with local wild species of junglefowl, forming genetically and geographically distinct groups.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Analysis of the most popular commercial breed shows that the White Leghorn breed possesses a mosaic of divergent ancestries inherited from different subspecies of red junglefowl.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Re-examination of bones from over 600 sites, and dating of those from 23 sites, identified the earliest probable chicken bones as from central Thailand, at Ban Non Wat, some 3,250 years ago.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The paleo-anatomist Joris Peters and the bioarchaeologist Greger Larson state that this coincided with the growing of rice, and propose that wild jungle fowl were attracted to eat the rice seeds, nested nearby, and became domesticated.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Skeletons of birds in the *Gallus* genus were used as grave goods at the site, confirming domestication.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] A word for the domestic chicken (**manuk*) is part of the reconstructed Proto-Austronesian language, indicating they were domesticated by the Austronesian peoples since ancient times.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens, together with dogs and pigs, were carried throughout the entire range of the prehistoric Austronesian maritime migrations to Island Southeast Asia, Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar, starting from at least 3000 BC from Taiwan.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] These chickens may have been introduced during pre-Columbian times to South America via Polynesian seafarers, but this is disputed.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens reached Egypt via the Middle East for purposes of cockfighting about 1400 BC and became widely bred in Egypt around 300 BC.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Three possible routes of introduction into Africa around the early first millennium AD could have been through the Egyptian Nile Valley, the East Africa Roman-Greek or Indian trade, or from Carthage and the Berbers, across the Sahara.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The earliest known remains are from Mali, Nubia, East Coast, and South Africa and date back to the middle of the first millennium AD.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The possibility that domestic chickens were in the Americas before Western contact is debated by researchers, but blue-egged chickens, found only in the Americas and Asia, suggest an Asian origin for early American chickens.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chicken bones from the Arauco Peninsula in south-central Chile were radiocarbon dated as pre-Columbian, and DNA analysis suggested they were related to prehistoric populations in Polynesia.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] However, further study of the same bones cast doubt on the findings.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chicken remains have been difficult to date, given the small and fragile bird bones; this may account for discrepancies in dates given by different sources.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Archaeological evidence is supplemented by mentions in historical texts from the last few centuries BC, and by depictions in prehistoric artworks, such as across Central Asia.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens were widespread throughout southern Central Asia by the 4th century BC.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Middle Eastern chicken remains go back to a little earlier than 2000 BC in Syria.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Phoenicians spread chickens along the Mediterranean coasts as far as Iberia.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] During the Hellenistic period (4th–2nd centuries BC), in the southern Levant, chickens began to be widely domesticated for food.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The first pictures of chickens in Europe are found on Corinthian pottery of the 7th century BC.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Breeding increased under the Roman Empire and reduced in the Middle Ages.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Genetic sequencing of chicken bones from archaeological sites in Europe revealed that in the High Middle Ages chickens became less aggressive and began to lay eggs earlier in the breeding season.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are susceptible both to parasites such as mites, and to diseases caused by pathogens such as bacteria and viruses.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The parasite *Dermanyssus gallinae* feeds on blood, causing irritation and reducing egg production, and acts as a vector for bacterial diseases such as salmonellosis and spirochaetosis.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are common and widespread domestic animals, with a total population of 23.7 billion as of 2018.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] More than 50 billion chickens are reared annually as a source of meat and eggs.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In the United States alone, more than 8 billion chickens are slaughtered each year for meat, and more than 300 million chickens are reared for egg production.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The vast majority of poultry is raised in factory farms.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] According to the Worldwatch Institute, 74% of the world's poultry meat and 68% of eggs are produced this way.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] An alternative to intensive poultry farming is free-range farming.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Friction between these two main methods has led to long-term issues of ethical consumerism.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Opponents of intensive farming argue that it harms the environment, creates human health risks and is inhumane towards sentient animals.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Advocates of intensive farming say that their efficient systems save land and food resources owing to increased productivity, and that the animals are looked after in a controlled environment.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens farmed for meat are called broilers.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Broiler breeds typically take less than six weeks to reach slaughter size, some weeks longer for free-range and organic broilers.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens farmed primarily for eggs are called layer hens.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The UK alone consumes more than 34 million eggs per day.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Hens of some breeds can produce over 300 eggs per year; the highest authenticated rate of egg-laying is 371 eggs in 364 days.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] After 12 months of laying, the commercial hen's egg-laying ability declines to the point where the flock is commercially unviable.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Hens, particularly from battery cage systems, are sometimes infirm or have lost a significant amount of their feathers, and their life expectancy has been reduced from around seven years to less than two years.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In the UK and Europe, laying hens are then slaughtered and used in processed foods, or sold as 'soup hens'.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In some other countries, flocks are sometimes force-moulted rather than being slaughtered to re-invigorate egg-laying.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] This involves complete withdrawal of food (and sometimes water) for 7–14 days or sufficiently long to cause a body weight loss of 25 to 35%, or up to 28 days under experimental conditions.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] This stimulates the hen to lose her feathers but also re-invigorates egg-production.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Some flocks may be force-moulted several times.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In 2003, more than 75% of all flocks were moulted in the US.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Keeping chickens as pets became increasingly popular in the 2000s among urban and suburban residents.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Many people obtain chickens for their egg production but often name them and treat them as any other pet like cats or dogs.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens provide companionship and have individual personalities.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] They eat from one's hand, jump onto one's lap, respond to and follow their handlers, and show affection.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are social, inquisitive, intelligent birds, and many people find their behaviour entertaining.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Certain breeds, such as silkies and many bantam varieties, are generally docile and are often recommended as good pets around children with disabilities.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] A cockfight is a contest held in a ring called a cockpit between two cocks.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Cockfighting is outlawed in many countries as involving cruelty to animals.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The activity seems to have been practised in the Indus Valley civilisation from 2500 to 2100 BC.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In the process of domestication, chickens were apparently kept initially for cockfighting, and only later used for food.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens have long been used as model organisms to study developing embryos.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Large numbers of embryos can be provided commercially; fertilized eggs can easily be opened and used to observe the developing embryo.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Equally important, embryologists can carry out experiments on such embryos, close the egg again and study the effects later in development.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] For instance, many important discoveries in limb development have been made using chicken embryos, such as the discovery of the apical ectodermal ridge and the zone of polarizing activity.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The chicken was the first bird species to have its genome sequenced.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] At 1.21 Gb, the chicken genome is similarly sized compared to other birds, but smaller than nearly all mammals: the human genome is 3.2 Gb.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The final gene set contained 26,640 genes (including noncoding genes and pseudogenes), with a total of 19,119 protein-coding genes, a similar number to the human genome.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In 2006, scientists researching the ancestry of birds switched on a chicken recessive gene, *talpid2*, and found that the embryo jaws initiated formation of teeth, like those found in ancient bird fossils.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens are featured widely in folklore, religion, literature, and popular culture.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The chicken is a sacred animal in many cultures and deeply embedded in belief systems and religious practices.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Roosters are sometimes used for divination, a practice called alectryomancy.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] This involves the sacrifice of a sacred rooster, often during a ritual cockfight, used as a form of communication with the gods.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] In Gabriel García Márquez's Nobel Prize-winning 1967 novel *One Hundred Years of Solitude*, cockfighting is outlawed in the town of Macondo after the patriarch of the Buendia family murders his cockfighting rival and is haunted by the man's ghost.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The pseudo-riddle "Why did the chicken cross the road?" dates to 1847, or earlier.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] Chickens have been featured in art in farmyard scenes such as Adriaen van Utrecht's 1646 *Turkeys and Chickens* and Walter Osborne's 1885 *Feeding the Chickens*.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The nursery rhyme "Cock a Doodle Doo", its chorus line imitating the cockerel's call, was published in *Mother Goose's Melody* in 1765.
[src:ayam-kampong/chicken] The 2000 animated adventure comedy film *Chicken Run*, directed by Peter Lord and Nick Park, featured anthropomorphic chickens with many chicken jokes.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A **crossbreed** is an organism with purebred parents of two different breeds, varieties, or populations.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A domestic animal of unknown ancestry, where the breed status of only one parent or grandparent is known, may also be called a crossbreed though the term "mixed breed" is technically more accurate.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Outcrossing is a type of crossbreeding used within a purebred breed to increase the genetic diversity within the breed, particularly when there is a need to avoid inbreeding.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] In animal breeding, *crossbreeds* are crosses within a single species, while *hybrids* are crosses between different species.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] In plant breeding terminology, the term *crossbreed* is uncommon, and no universal term is used to distinguish hybridization or crossing within a population from those between populations, or even those between species.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Crossbreeding is the process of breeding such an organism.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] It can be beneficially used to maintain health and viability of organisms.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] However, irresponsible crossbreeding can also produce organisms of inferior quality or dilute a purebred gene pool to the point of extinction of a given breed of organism.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A *crossbred* dog is a cross between two (sometimes more) known breeds, and is usually distinguished from a *mixed-breed dog*, which has ancestry from many sources, some of which may not be known.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Crossbreeds are popular, due to the belief that they have increased vigor without loss of attractiveness of the dog.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Certain planned crossbreeding between purebred dogs of different breeds are now widely known as "designer dogs" and can produce puppies worth more than their purebred parents, due to a high demand.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A hybrid animal is one with parentage of two separate species, differentiating it from crossbred animals, which have parentage of the same species.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Hybrids are usually, but not always, sterile.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] One of the most ancient types of hybrid animal is the mule, a cross between a female horse and a male donkey.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] The liger is a hybrid cross between a male lion and female tiger.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] The yattle is a cross between a cow and a yak.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Other crosses include the tigon (between a male tiger and female lion) and yakalo (between a yak and an American bison).
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] The Incas recognized that hybrids of *Lama glama* (llama) and *Vicugna pacos* (alpaca) resulted in a hybrid with none of the advantages of either parent.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] At one time it was thought that dogs and wolves were separate species, and the crosses between dogs and wolves were called wolf hybrids.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Today wolves and dogs are both recognized as *Canis lupus*, but the old term "wolf hybrid" is still used.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A mixed-breed animal is defined as having undocumented or unknown parentage, while a crossbreed generally has known, usually purebred parents of two distinct breeds or varieties.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A dog of unknown parentage is often called a mixed-breed dog, "mutt" or "mongrel." A cat of unknown parentage is often referred to as a domestic short-haired or domestic long-haired cat generically, and in some dialects is often called a "moggie".
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A horse of unknown bloodlines is called a grade horse.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] A designer crossbreed or designer breed is a crossbred animal with purebred parents, usually registered with a breed registry, but from two different breeds.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] These animals are the result of a deliberate decision to create a specific crossbred animal.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Less often, the animal may have more than two pure breeds in its ancestry, but unlike a mutt or a mongrel, its entire pedigree is known to descend from specific known animals.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] While the term is best known when applied to certain dog crossbreeds, other animals such as cattle, horses, birds and cats may also be bred in this fashion.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Some crossbred breeders start a freestanding breed registry to record designer crossbreds, other crossbreds may be included in an "appendix" to an existing purebred registry. either form of registration may be the first step in recording and tracking pedigrees in order to develop a new breed.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] 5. as the preliminary steps toward developing a new animal breed.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Breeders of designer crossbreds borrow the technical language from hybrid plant breeding: A first generation, 50–50 crossbred is an F1 cross.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] An F2 cross bred to an F2 cross creates an F3 cross.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Similarly, an F2 animal bred to an F1 animal creates an F2b backcross.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] F3 crosses and greater are called "multi-generational" crosses.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] In dog breeding, three generations of reliable documented breeding can be considered a "breed" rather than a crossbreed.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] There are disadvantages to creating designer crossbreeds, notably the potential that the cross will be of inferior quality or that it will not produce as consistent a result as would breeding purebred animals.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] For example, the Poodle is a frequent breed used in creation of designer crossbreeds, due to its non-shedding coat, but that trait does not always breed true when it is part of a designer cross.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] Also, because breeders of crossbred animals may be less careful about genetic testing and weeding out undesirable traits, certain deleterious dominant genes may still be passed on to a crossbreed offspring.
[src:ayam-kampong/cross-breeding] In an F2 cross, recessive genetic traits may also return if the parent animals were both carriers of an undesired trait.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The **Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations** (**FAO**) is a specialized agency of the United Nations that leads international efforts to defeat hunger and improve nutrition and food security.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Its Latin motto, *fiat panis*, translates to "let there be bread".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It was founded on 16 October 1945 in Quebec City, Canada.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO comprises 194 members, including 193 countries and one member organization, the European Union (EU).
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Its headquarters is in Rome, Italy, and it maintains regional and field offices worldwide, operating in over 130 countries.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It helps governments and development agencies coordinate their activities to improve and develop agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and land and water resources.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It also conducts research, provides technical assistance to projects, operates educational and training programs, and collects agricultural output, production, and development data.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO is governed by a biennial conference representing each member country and the EU, which elects a 49-member executive council.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The director-general, as of 2019 Qu Dongyu of China, serves as the chief administrative officer.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Various committees govern matters such as finance, programs, agriculture, and fisheries.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The idea of an international organization for food and agriculture emerged in the late 19th and early 20th century, advanced primarily by Polish-born American agriculturalist and activist David Lubin.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In May–June 1905, an international conference was held in Rome, Italy, which led to the creation of the International Institute of Agriculture (IIA) by the King of Italy, Victor Emmanuel III.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The IIA was the first intergovernmental organization to deal with the problems and challenges of agriculture on a global scale.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It worked primarily to collect, compile, and publish data on agriculture, ranging from output statistics to a catalog of crop diseases.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Among its achievements was the publication of the first agricultural census in 1930.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] During the war, in 1943, United States president Franklin D.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Roosevelt called a League of Nations Conference on Food and Agriculture, which brought representatives from forty-four governments to The Omni Homestead Resort in Hot Springs, Virginia, from 18 May to 3 June to attend the Hot Springs Conference.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The main impetus for the conference was the British-born Australian economist Frank L.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] McDougall, who since 1935 had advocated for an international forum to address hunger and malnutrition.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Conference ended with a commitment to establish a permanent organization for food and agriculture, which was achieved on 16 October 1945 in Quebec City, Canada, following the Constitution of the Food and Agriculture Organization.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The first session of the FAO Conference began the same day in the Château Frontenac in Quebec City and ended on 1 November 1945.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] This was led by Sir John Boyd Orr where his work on ending world hunger and creation of FAO resulted in him winning the Nobel Peace Prize in 1949.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] After the war, the IIA was officially dissolved by resolution of its Permanent Committee on 27 February 1948.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Its functions, facilities, and mandate were then transferred to the newly established FAO, which maintained its headquarters in Rome.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO's initial functions supported agricultural and nutrition research and provided technical assistance to member countries to boost production in agriculture, fishery, and forestry.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Beginning in the 1960s, it focused on efforts to develop high-yield strains of grain, eliminate protein deficiency, promote rural employment, and increase agricultural exports.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO recognized the decrease of these resources as an urgent problem in 1961 and created a joint collaboration with the International Biological Program (IBP) in 1967.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] To that end, it joined the UN General Assembly in creating the UN World Food Programme, the largest humanitarian organization addressing hunger and promoting food security.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO launched what would become the FAO Money and Medals Programme (MMP) in 1968.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO issued collector art medals in various series to bring attention to FAO's goals and missions.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] This program was responsible for over a hundred medal designs issued to the collecting public.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] A thirtieth anniversary medal of the MMP was issued in 1998.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In 1974, in response to famine in Africa, the FAO convened the first World Food Summit to address widespread hunger, malnutrition, and food insecurity.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The meeting resulted in a proclamation that "every man, woman, and child has the inalienable right to be free from hunger and malnutrition to develop their physical and mental faculties" and a global commitment to eradicate these issues within a decade.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] A subsequent summit in 1996 addressed the shortcomings in achieving this goal while establishing a strategic plan for eliminating hunger and malnutrition into the 21st century.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Every year, FAO publishes a number of major 'State of the World' reports related to food, agriculture, forestry, fisheries and natural resources.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In 1951, the FAO's headquarters were moved from Washington, D.C., United States, to Rome, Italy.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The agency is directed by the Conference of Member Nations, which meets every two years to review the work carried out by the organization and to Work and Budget for the next two-year period.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The conference elects a council of 49 member states (serve three-year rotating terms) that acts as an interim governing body, and the director-general, who heads the agency.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO is composed of eight departments: Agriculture and Consumer Protection, Climate, Biodiversity, Land and Water Department, Economic and Social Development, Fisheries and Aquaculture, Forestry, Corporate Services and Technical Cooperation and Programme Management.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Beginning in 1994, the FAO underwent the most significant restructuring since its founding, to decentralize operations, streamline procedures and reduce costs.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] As a result, savings of about US$50 million, €43 million a year were realized.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO's Regular Programme budget is funded by its members through contributions set at the FAO Conference.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] This budget covers core technical work, cooperation and partnerships including the Technical Cooperation Programme, knowledge exchange, policy and advocacy, direction and administration, governance and security.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The total FAO Budget planned for 2018–2019 is US$1,005.6 million.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The voluntary contributions provided by members and other partners support mechanical and emergency (including rehabilitation) assistance to governments for clearly defined purposes linked to the results framework, as well as direct support to FAO's core work.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The voluntary contributions are expected to reach approximately US$1.6 billion in 2016–2017.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The world headquarters is located in Rome, in the former seat of the Department of Italian East Africa.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] One of the most notable features of the building was the Axum Obelisk which stood in front of the agency seat, although just outside the territory allocated to the FAO by the Italian Government.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It was taken from Ethiopia by Benito Mussolini's troops in 1937 as war booty and returned on 18 April 2005.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Partnership and Liaison Offices provide for stronger country participation in the FAO's work and programmes at national, sub-regional, regional, and inter-regional levels, and enhanced cooperation through unilateral trust fund projects and South–South cooperation.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO has outlined the following priorities in its fight against hunger.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Two fundamental areas of work – gender and governance – are fully integrated in the above strategic objective action plans.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO and the World Health Organization created the Codex Alimentarius Commission in 1961 to develop food standards, guidelines, and texts such as codes of practice under the Joint FAO/WHO Food Standards Programme.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The programme's main aims are protecting consumer health, ensuring fair trade, and promoting co-ordination of all food standards work undertaken by intergovernmental and non-governmental organizations.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In 1996, FAO organized the World Food Summit, attended by 112 Heads or Deputy Heads of State and Government.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Summit concluded with the signing of the Rome Declaration, which established the goal of halving the number of people who suffer from hunger by 2015.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] At the same time, 1,200 civil society organizations (CSOs) from 80 countries participated in an NGO forum.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The forum was critical of the growing industrialization of agriculture and called upon governments – and FAO – to do more to protect the 'Right to Food' for the poor.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In 1997, FAO launched TeleFood, a campaign of concerts, sporting events, and other activities to harness the power of media, celebrities, and concerned citizens to help fight hunger.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Since its start, the campaign has generated close to US$28 million, €15 million in donations.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Money raised through TeleFood pays for small, sustainable projects that help small-scale farmers produce more food for their families and communities.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The projects provide tangible resources, such as fishing equipment, seeds, and agricultural implements.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] They vary enormously, from helping families raise pigs in Venezuela through creating school gardens in Cape Verde and Mauritania or providing school lunches in Uganda and teaching children to grow food to raising fish in a leper community in India.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO Goodwill Ambassadors Programme was initiated in 1999.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It was created to increase public awareness and disseminate information about issues related to food security and hunger in the world.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In 2004 the Right to Food Guidelines were adopted which offer guidance to states on how to implement their obligations on the right to food.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In December 2007, FAO launched its Initiative on soaring food prices to help small producers raise their output and earn more.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Under the initiative, FAO contributed to the work of the UN High-Level Task Force on the Global Food Crisis, which produced the Comprehensive Framework for Action.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In May 2009, FAO and the European Union signed an initial aid package worth €125 million to support small farmers in countries hit hard by rising food prices.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The aid package falls under the EU's €1 billion Food Facility, set up with the UN Secretary-General's High-Level Task Force on the Global Food Crisis and FAO to focus on programmes that will have a quick but lasting impact on food security.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO is receiving around €200 million for work in 25 countries, of which €15.4 million goes to Zimbabwe.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Special Programme for Food Security is FAO's flagship initiative for reaching the goal of halving the number of hungry in the world by 2015 (currently estimated at close to 1 billion people) as part of its commitment to the Millennium Development Goals.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Through projects in over 100 countries worldwide, the programme promotes effective, tangible solutions to eliminating hunger, undernourishment, and poverty.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Currently, 102 countries are engaged in the programme, and of these, approximately 30 have begun shifting from pilot to national programmes.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] To maximize the impact of its work, FAO strongly promotes national ownership and local empowerment in the countries in which it operates.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The 1billionhungry project became the EndingHunger campaign in April 2011.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Spearheaded by FAO in partnership with other UN agencies and private nonprofit groups, the EndingHunger movement pushes the boundaries of conventional public advocacy.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It builds on the success in 2010 of The 1billonhungry project and the subsequent chain of public events that led to the collection of over three million signatures on a global petition to end hunger (www.EndingHunger.org).
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The petition was originally presented to representatives of world governments at a ceremony in Rome on 30 November 2010.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The web and partnerships are two pivotal and dynamic aspects of EndingHunger.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The campaign relies on the assistance of organizations and institutions that can facilitate the project's diffusion, by placing banners on their own websites or organizing events aimed to raise awareness of the project.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In its 2011 season, the campaign expanded its multimedia content, pursued mutual visibility arrangements with partner organizations, and sharpened its focus on 14- to 25-year-olds, who were encouraged to understand their potential as a social movement to push for the end of hunger.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Moreover, the EndingHunger project is a viral communication campaign, renewing and expanding its efforts to build the movement through Facebook, Twitter and other social networks.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Those who sign the petition can spread the link of the EndingHunger website to their friends, via social media or mail, in order to gain awareness and signatures for the petition.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The next interim objective is to grow the EndingHunger movement's Facebook community to 1 million members.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The original 1billionhungry campaign borrowed as its slogan the line "I'm as mad as hell, and I'm not going to take this anymore!", used by Peter Finch in the 1976 film, *Network*.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Meanwhile, the yellow whistle has been the campaign symbol from the start, from 1billionhungry to Ending Hunger.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] (The creative concept was provided by the McCann Erickson Italy Communication Agency.) It symbolizes the fact that we are "blowing the whistle" on the silent disaster of hunger.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It is both a symbol and – at many live events taking place around the world – a physical means of expressing frustration and making some noise about the hunger situation.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Both The 1billionhungry and the EndingHunger campaigns have continued to attract UN Goodwill Ambassadors from the worlds of music and cinema, literature, sport, activism and government.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO created the International Plant Protection Convention or IPPC in 1952.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] This international treaty organization works to prevent the international spread of pests and plant diseases in both cultivated and wild plants.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Among its functions are the maintenance of lists of plant pests, tracking of pest outbreaks, and coordination of technical assistance between member nations.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] As of July 2018, 183 contracting parties have ratified the treaty.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO is depositary of the International Treaty on Plant Genetic Resources for Food and Agriculture, also called *Plant Treaty*, *Seed Treaty* or *ITPGRFA*, entered into force on 29 June 2004.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Alliance Against Hunger and Malnutrition (AAHM) aims to address how countries and organizations can be more effective in advocating and carrying out actions to address hunger and malnutrition.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] As a global partnership, AAHM creates global connections between local, regional, national and international institutions that share the goals of fighting hunger and malnutrition.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The organization works to address food security by enhancing resources and knowledge sharing and strengthening hunger activities within countries and across state lines at the regional and international levels.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Following the World Food Summit, the Alliance was initially created in 2002 as the 'International Alliance Against Hunger (IAAH)' to strengthen and coordinate national efforts in the fight against hunger and malnutrition.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The mission of the Alliance originates from the first and eighth UN Millennium Development Goals; reducing the number of people that suffer from hunger in half by 2015 (preceded by the "Rome Declaration" in 1996) and developing a global partnership for development.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Alliance was founded by the Rome-based food agencies – the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), UN World Food Programme (WFP), International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD), – and Bioversity International.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] AAHM connects top-down and bottom-up anti-hunger development initiatives, linking governments, UN organizations, and NGOs together in order to increase effectiveness through unity.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] During the 1990s, FAO took a leading role in the promotion of integrated pest management for rice production in Asia.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Hundreds of thousands of farmers were trained using an approach known as the Farmer Field School (FFS).
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Like many of the programmes managed by FAO, the funds for Farmer Field Schools came from bilateral Trust Funds, with Australia, Netherlands, Norway and Switzerland acting as the leading donors.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO's efforts in this area have drawn praise from NGOs that have otherwise criticized much of the work of the organization.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO established an *Emergency Prevention System for Transboundary Animal and Plant Pests and Diseases* in 1994, focusing on the control of diseases like rinderpest, foot-and-mouth disease and avian flu by helping governments coordinate their responses.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] One key element is the *Global Rinderpest Eradication Programme*, which has advanced to a stage where large tracts of Asia and Africa have now been free of the cattle disease rinderpest for an extended period of time.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Meanwhile, the *Desert Locust Information Service* monitors the worldwide locust situation and keeps affected countries and donors informed of expected developments.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Global Partnership Initiative for Plant Breeding Capacity Building (GIPB) is a global partnership dedicated to increasing plant breeding capacity building.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The mission of GIPB is to enhance the capacity of developing countries to improve crops for food security and sustainable development through better plant breeding and delivery systems.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The ultimate goal is to ensure that a critical mass of plant breeders, leaders, managers and technicians, donors and partners are linked together through an effective global network.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Increasing capacity building for plant breeding in developing countries is critical for the achievement of meaningful results in poverty and hunger reduction and to reverse the current worrisome trends.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Plant breeding is a well recognized science capable of widening the genetic and adaptability base of cropping systems, by combining conventional selection techniques and modern technologies.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It is essential to face and prevent the recurrence of crises such as that of the soaring food prices and to respond to the increasing demands for crop based sources of energy.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO's technical cooperation department hosts an Investment Centre that promotes greater investment in agriculture and rural development by helping developing countries identify and formulate sustainable agricultural policies, programmes and projects.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It mobilizes funding from multilateral institutions such as the World Bank, regional development banks and international funds as well as FAO resources.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] This UN Partnership Initiative aims to identify, support and safeguard Globally Important Agricultural Heritage Systems and their livelihoods, agricultural and associated biodiversity, landscapes, knowledge systems and cultures around the world.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The GIAHS Partnership recognizes the crucial importance of the well-being of family farming communities in an integrated approach while directing activities towards sustainable agriculture and rural development.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Commission on Genetic Resources for Food and Agriculture, established in 1983, provides an intergovernmental forum that specifically addresses biological diversity for food and agriculture.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Its main objective is to ensure the sustainable use and conservation of biodiversity for food and agriculture and the fair and equitable sharing of benefits derived from its use, for present and future generations.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO has a unit focused on Animal Genetic Resources, which are defined as "those animal species that are used, or may be used, for the production of food and agriculture, and the populations within each of them.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO supports a variety of *ex situ* and *in situ* conservation strategies including cryoconservation of animal genetic resources.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] One of FAO's strategic goals is the sustainable management of the world's forests.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The *Forestry Division* works to balance social and environmental considerations with the economic needs of rural populations living in forest areas.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO serves as a neutral forum for policy dialogue, as a reliable source of information on forests and trees and as a provider of expert technical assistance and advice to help countries develop and implement effective national forest programmes.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FAO is both a global clearinghouse for information on forests and forest resources and a facilitator that helps building countries' local capacity to provide their own national forest data.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In collaboration with member countries, FAO carries out periodic global assessments of forest resources, which are made available through reports, publications and the FAO's Web site.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The *Global Forest Resources Assessment* provides comprehensive reporting on forests worldwide every five years.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] FRA 2020 is the most recent global assessment.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The results, data and analyses are available online in different formats, including key findings, main report and country reports.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Every two years, FAO publishes the *State of the World's Forests*, a major report covering current and emerging issues facing the forestry sector.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Since 1947, FAO has published the FAO Yearbook of Forest Products, a compilation of statistical data on basic forest products from over 100 countries and territories of the world.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It contains data on the volume of production; and the volume, value and direction of trade in forest products.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO is an official sponsor of International Day of Forests, on 21 March each year, as proclaimed by the United Nations General Assembly on 28 November 2012.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Every six years since 1926, FAO and a host member state hold the World Forestry Congress.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It is a forum for the sharing of knowledge and experience regarding the conservation, management and use of the world's forests, and covers such issues as international dialogue, socio-economic and institutional aspects, and forest policies.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Forestry Department is also organized geographically in several groups covering the whole world's forest ecosystems.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] One of them is the Silva Mediterranean work-group, covering the pan-Mediterranean region.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] At the World Forum on Urban Forests in October 2018, the FAO and the Arbor Day Foundation jointly launched the Tree Cities of the World programme.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The aim of this programme is to celebrate and recognize cities and towns of all sizes throughout the world which have shown a commitment to maintaining their urban forests.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] From the end of 2019, any municipality which has responsibility for its trees was able to apply to join Tree Cities of the World.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] On 4 February 2020, 59 cities were announced as having achieved the designation of Tree City of the World.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] There were 27 in the United States, with the rest scattered across the world.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The work of the Fisheries and Aquaculture Department centers on the "Sustainable management and use of fisheries and aquaculture resource", embracing normative as well as operational activities, whether implemented from headquarters or from the field.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The FAO *Code of Conduct for Responsible Fisheries* was adopted in 1995.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Land and Water Division maintains a database of global water statistics, Aquastat.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The Fisheries and Aquaculture Division maintains a database of global Fisheries and Aquaculture statistics, FishStat.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] As of 1 May 2020, the Organization has 194 Member Nations, one Member Organization, and two Associate Members.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Taiwan (at the time representing China), withdrew from the FAO in 1951. in 1971, the People's Republic of China was recognized as the representative of China by the FAO and the withdrawal from part of Taiwan was not taken into account.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The only UN member state that is a non-member of the FAO is Liechtenstein.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Both UN observer states are also non-members of the FAO: the Holy See (Vatican City) and Palestine.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Some countries may denote specific representatives to the FAO, for instance the United States Ambassador to the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, who has ambassador rank and is also a part of the United States Mission to the UN Agencies in Rome.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] There has been public criticism of FAO for at least 30 years.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] At the same time, the World Food Programme, which started as an experimental three-year programme under FAO, was growing in size and independence, with the Directors of FAO and WFP struggling for power.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] State Department expressed the view that "The Food and Agriculture Organization has lagged behind other UN organizations in responding to US desires for improvements in program and budget processes to enhance value for money spent".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] A year later, in 1991, *The Ecologist* magazine produced a special issue under the heading "The UN Food and Agriculture Organization: Promoting World Hunger".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The magazine included articles that questioned FAO's policies and practices in forestry, fisheries, aquaculture, and pest control.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The articles were written by experts such as Helena Norberg-Hodge, Vandana Shiva, Edward Goldsmith, Miguel A.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The 2002 Food Summit organized by FAO was considered to have been ineffectual and unproductive by the official participants.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Social movements, farmers, fisherfolk, pastoralists, indigenous peoples, environmentalists, women's organizations, trade unions and NGOs expressed their "collective disappointment in, and rejection of the official Declaration of the ...
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In 2004, FAO produced a controversial report called "Agricultural Biotechnology: meeting the needs of the poor?", which claimed that "agricultural biotechnology has real potential as a new tool in the war on hunger".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In response to the report, more than 650 organizations from around the world signed an open letter in which they said "FAO has broken its commitment to civil society and peasants' organisations".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Jacques Diouf, the Director General of FAO at that time, responded immediately, stating that decisions on biotechnology must "be taken at the international level by competent bodies" (in other words, not by non-governmental organizations).
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In May 2006, a British newspaper published the resignation letter of Louise Fresco, one of eight Assistant Directors-General of FAO.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In her letter, Fresco stated that "the Organization has been unable to adapt to a new era", that its "contribution and reputation have declined steadily" and "its leadership has not proposed bold options to overcome this crisis".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The 32nd Session of FAO's Committee on World Food Security in 2006, attended by 120 countries, was widely criticized by non-governmental organizations, but largely ignored by the mainstream media.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Oxfam called for an end to the talk-fests while Via Campesina issued a statement that criticised FAO's policy of Food Security.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] On 18 October 2007, the final report of an Independent External Evaluation of FAO was published.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] More than 400 pages in length, the evaluation was the first of its kind in the history of the Organization.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It had been commissioned by decision of the 33rd Session of the FAO Conference in November 2005.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The report concluded that "The Organization is today in a financial and programme crisis" but "the problems affecting the Organization today can all be solved".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Among the problems noted by the IEE were: "The Organization has been conservative and slow to adapt"; "FAO currently has a heavy and costly bureaucracy", and "The capacity of the Organization is declining and many of its core competencies are now imperilled".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Among the solutions offered were: "A new Strategic Framework", "institutional culture change and reform of administrative and management systems".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In conclusion the IEE stated that, "If FAO did not exist it would need to be invented".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The official response from FAO came on 29 October 2007.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] It indicated that management supported the principal conclusion in the report of the IEE on the need for "reform with growth" so as to have an FAO "fit for this century".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Meanwhile, hundreds of FAO staff signed a petition in support of the IEE recommendations, calling for "a radical shift in management culture and spirit, depoliticization of appointments, restoration of trust between staff and management, [and] setting strategic priorities of the organization".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In May 2008, while talking about the ongoing world food crisis, President Abdoulaye Wade of Senegal expressed the opinion that FAO was "a waste of money" and that "we must scrap it".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Wade said that FAO was itself largely to blame for the price rises, and that the organization's work was duplicated by other bodies that operated more efficiently, like the UN's International Fund for Agricultural Development.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] However, this criticism may have had more to do with personal animosity between the President and the Director-General, himself a Senegalese, particularly in light of the significant differences in the work carried out by the two organizations.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In June 2008, the FAO sponsored the High-Level Conference on World Food Security.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The summit was notable for the lack of agreement over the issue of biofuels.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In November 2008, a Special Conference of FAO member countries agreed a US$42.6 million (€38.6 million), three-year Immediate Plan of Action for "reform with growth", as recommended by the IEE.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Under the plan US$21.8 million would be spent on overhauling the financial procedures, hierarchies and human resources management.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] From 2013, an English-language newspaper based in Rome, *The Italian Insider*, made several allegations of nepotism and corruption within FAO and reported on poor management-staff relations.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In June 2018, FAO and four of its officials took the paper and its editor, John Philips, to court alleging defamation, using a law dating back to the fascist era in Italy.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Reporters Without Borders condemned "the disproportionate nature of the defamation proceedings", for which the newspaper was liable for a fine of up to Euros 100,000 and the editor at least three years in prison.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The case was adjourned until January 2019, when it was further adjourned until May 2019.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The January hearing was considered by the British satirical magazine *Private Eye* to have been "one of the more surreal courtroom scenes in modern times", involving dispute as to the meaning of an English slang word used by the *Insider*.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] In 2016/17 FAO was heavily criticized for recruiting Nadine Heredia Alarcón de Humala, wife of the former president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, to a senior position, at a time when she was being investigated by Peru following corruption allegations.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Critics included Transparency International.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] At the end of April 2017, FAO staff unions addressed the organization's Governing Council to complain about the practice of issuing short-term contracts that "exploit employees without providing job security, social security and paid leave".
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] Other complaints included the increasing centralization of management processes, despite claims that FAO was being decentralized, and the failure to follow United Nations recommendations regarding increasing the retirement age.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] The staff representative also complained about the high percentage of unfilled positions, increasing the workload for others who were under pressure to deliver more with less.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] She also noted that contacts between Management and the staff bodies were becoming less and less frequent.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p01] An investigation by the German public broadcaster ARD shows that the Chinese leadership of the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation FAO has tailored it to Chinese interests since Qu Dongyu took office in 2019.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] The FAO Conference in November 2007 unanimously welcomed the IEE report and established a Conference Committee for the Follow-up to the Independent External Evaluation of FAO (CoC-IEE) to be chaired by the Independent Chairperson of Council, and open to full participation by all Members.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] The CoC-IEE was charged to review the IEE report and its recommendations and develop an Immediate Plan of Action (IPA) for their implementation.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] A comprehensive programme of organizational reform and culture change began in 2008 after the release of an Independent External Evaluation.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] Headquarters restructuring and delegation of decision making created a flatter more responsive structure and reduced costs.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] Modernizing and streamlining of administrative and operational processes took place.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] Improved internal teamwork and closer external partnerships coupled with upgrading of IT infrastructure and greater autonomy of FAO's decentralized offices now allows the Organization to respond quickly where needs are greatest.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] As FAO is primarily a knowledge based organization, investing in human resources is a top priority.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] Capacity building including a leadership programme, employee rotation and a new junior professional programme were established.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] Individual performance management, an ethics and ombudsman officer and an independent office of evaluation were designed to improve performance through learning and strengthened oversight.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] In January 2012, the Director-General José Graziano da Silva acted upon the commitment made during his campaign to bring the FAO reform to a successful and anticipated completion.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] In addition, the new Director-General shifted the focus of the reform process to realization of its benefits and mainstreaming the reform into the work of the Organization.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] In July 2020, the FAO Council approved a series of measures proposed by its Director-General Qu Dongyu to modernize the organization and make it more efficient and effective.
[src:ayam-kampong/food-and-agriculture-organization-p02] An important element within the approved measures is the adoption "of a more flexible organizational structure, aimed at ensuring agility, optimal cross-sectoral collaboration and better responses to emerging needs and priorities".
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] The term is used in two senses that do not overlap completely: as a farmer-centric description of husbandry methods, and as a consumer-centric description of them.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] There is a diet where the practitioner only eats meat from free-range sources called ethical omnivorism.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In ranching, free-range livestock are permitted to roam without being fenced in, as opposed to intensive animal farming practices such as the concentrated animal feeding operation.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In many agriculture-based economies, free-range livestock are quite common.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] If one allows "free range" to include "herding", free range was a typical husbandry method at least until the development of barbed wire and chicken wire.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In the case of poultry, free range is the dominant system until the discovery of vitamins A and D in the 1920s, which allowed confinement to be practised successfully on a commercial scale.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Before that, green feed and sunshine (for the vitamin D) were necessary to provide the necessary vitamin content.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Some large commercial breeding flocks were reared on pasture into the 1950s.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Nutritional science resulted in the increased use of confinement for other livestock species in much the same way.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Extended grazing on open grasslands can stimulate plant growth that sequesters additional carbon dioxide.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] However, grass-fed cows generally grow more slowly and are smaller at slaughter compared to grain-fed cows.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Because they take longer to reach market weight and convert feed into meat less efficiently, their total lifetime emissions—particularly methane—are typically higher.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] As a result, grass-fed beef tends to have a higher carbon footprint per kilogram than grain-fed beef.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] A study by Daniel Blaustein-Rejto and colleagues estimated that emissions from grass-fed beef were approximately 20% higher than those from grain-fed cattle.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Compared to caged hens, free-range hens produce fewer eggs and required more feed, which resulted in a carbon footprint around 16% higher per kilogram of egg.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In the United States, the Department of Agriculture free range regulations currently apply only to poultry and indicate that the animal has been allowed access to the outside.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] To be considered "free range," the poultry must have access to the outdoors for more than 51% of the animal's life.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] However, USDA regulations make no mention of the quality or size of the outside range.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] The Certified Humane Program offers third-party certification for producers who meet minimum standards, including providing access to grass pastures, traditional nests, and "dust areas to perform natural behaviors".
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] The term "free range" is mainly used as a marketing term rather than a husbandry term, meaning something on the order of, "low stocking density", "pasture-raised", "grass-fed", "old-fashioned", "humanely raised", etc.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] There have been proposals to regulate USDA labeling of products as free range within the United States.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] As of 2017 what constitutes raising an animal "free range" is almost entirely decided by the producer of that product, and is frequently inconsistent with consumer ideas of what the term means.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In poultry-keeping, "free range" is widely confused with yarding, which means keeping poultry in fenced yards.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Yarding, as well as floorless portable chicken pens ("chicken tractors") may have some of the benefits of free-range livestock but, in reality, the methods have little in common with the free-range method.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] A behavioral definition of free range is perhaps the most useful: "chickens kept with a fence that restricts their movements very little." This has practical implications.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Department of Agriculture Food Safety and Inspection Service (FSIS) requires that chickens raised for their meat have access to the outside in order to receive the free-range certification.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] However, what qualifies as "access" is not defined.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] There is no requirement for access to pasture, and there may be access to only dirt or gravel.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Free-range chicken eggs, however, have no legal definition in the United States.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Likewise, free-range egg producers have no common standard on what the term means.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] The broadness of "free range" in the U.S. has caused some people to look for alternative terms.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] "Pastured poultry" is a term promoted by farmer/author Joel Salatin for broiler chickens raised on grass pasture for all of their lives except for the initial brooding period.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] The Pastured Poultry concept is promoted by the American Pastured Poultry Producers' Association (APPPA), an organization of farmers raising their poultry using Salatin's principles.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] This term is not defined by the USDA and has no legal definition.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] To use a term like pasture-raised, producers must submit documentation to the FSIS of continuous free access to the outdoors, but do not need to include additional terminology to define pasture-raised on its label.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Traditional American usage equates "free range" with "unfenced", and with the implication that there was no herdsman keeping them together or managing them in any way.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Legally, a free-range jurisdiction allowed livestock (perhaps only of a few named species) to run free, and the owner was not liable for any damage they caused.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In such jurisdictions, people who wished to avoid damage by livestock had to fence them out; in others, the owners had to fence them in.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Department of Agriculture (USDA) has no specific definition for "free-range" beef, pork, and other non-poultry products.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] All USDA definitions of "free-range" refer specifically to poultry.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In a December 2002 Federal Register notice and request for comments (67 Fed.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] 79552), the USDA's Agricultural Marketing Service proposed "minimum requirements for livestock and meat industry production/marketing claims".
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Many industry claim categories are included in the notice, including breed claims, antibiotic claims, and grain fed claims.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] "Free Range, Free Roaming, or Pasture Raised" would be defined as "livestock that have had continuous and unconfined access to pasture throughout their life cycle" with an exception for swine ("continuous access to pasture for at least 80% of their production cycle").
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In a May 2006 Federal Register notice (71 Fed.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] 27662), the agency presented a summary and its responses to comments received in the 2002 notice, but only for the category "grass (forage) fed" which the agency stated was to be a category separate from "free range".
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Comments received for other categories, including "free range", are to be published in future Federal Register editions.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] There are EU regulations about what free-range means for laying hens and broilers (meat chickens) as indicated above.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] However, there are no EU regulations for free-range pork, so pigs could be indoors for some of their lives.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In order to be classified as free-range, animals must have access to the outdoors for at least part of their lives.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Australian standards in relation to free-range production are largely espoused in third-party certification trade marks due to the absence of any significant legally binding legislation.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] A number of certification bodies are utilised by rearers to identify their products with a particular level of animal welfare standards.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In events where producers do not choose to use a certified trade mark and merely state that their product is 'free range', the producer is bound by consumer expectations and perceptions of what constitutes free range.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Producers are generally thought to be bound to Model Codes of Practice of Animal Welfare published by the CSIRO, and in some states this forms part of legislation.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In Australia, three farming methods for the production of eggs are utilised.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In 2011, traditional cage (or battery) eggs accounted for 42% of value, barn-laid eggs account for 10% of value, free-range eggs accounted for 44% of value, and organic eggs accounted for 4% of value.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] Increased demand for free range eggs due to customer concerns over animal welfare has led to a number of different standards developing in relation to three core welfare measures – indoor stocking density, outdoor stocking density, and beak trimming.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] The above standards are not always met, and on some occasions producers may want more ethical standards.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] As such, certified trade marks play a significant role in the determining of what constitutes free range.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] In Australia, free range and organic chicken accounts for about 16.6% of value in the poultry market.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] This percentage is expected to grow to up to 25% in the next 5 years.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] No meat birds are raised in cages in Australia.
[src:ayam-kampong/free-range] There are three main certification trademarks in this market.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is one of Malaysia's most important economic hubs, having the highest gross domestic product in Malaysia outside of the Klang Valley, making it the country's second largest state economy.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Its household income and total salaries are also the second highest among all Malaysian states.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor has the world's second largest artificial intelligence hub, robust manufacturing and logistics centres, and home to the Port of Tanjung Pelepas, the 15th busiest port in the world.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Located in southern Johor, Iskandar Malaysia is Malaysia's largest special economic zone by investment value.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor's history began with the Johor Sultanate, which emerged as a rump state of the Malacca Sultanate.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It operated as a sovereign state until the arrival of European powers, when the Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1824 divided the wider polity between the British and the Dutch and fixed Johor's modern boundaries.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor remained largely self-governing until 1885, when British oversight increased through the appointment of a General Adviser who directed all affairs over the Sultan apart from matters of local religion and customs.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor became a British protected state within the Unfederated Malay States in 1914, a position interrupted only by the Japanese occupation of Malaya.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] After the war, it joined the Malayan Union in 1946 and subsequently the Federation of Malaya in 1948, the latter of which gained its independence from the British in 1957, before entering modern-day Malaysia under the Malaysia Agreement of 1963.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor has high diversity in ethnicity, culture, language, and is known for its traditional dance of *zapin* and *kuda kepang*.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The head of state is the Sultan of Johor, while the head of government is the Chief Minister.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The government system is closely modelled on the Westminster system.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is divided into administrative districts, with Johor Bahru District being the second largest district in Malaysia by population and economy.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Islam is the state religion, but other religions can be freely practised.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor has diverse tropical rainforests and an equatorial climate.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Situated at the southern foothills of the Tenasserim Hills, inselbergs and massifs dominate the state's flat landscape, with Mount Ledang being the highest point.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The area was first known to the northern inhabitants of Siam as *Gangganu* or *Ganggayu* (Treasury of Gems) due to the abundance of gemstones near the Johor River.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Arab traders referred to it as جَوْهَر‎ (‏*jauhar*‎), a word borrowed from the Persian گوهر‎ (*gauhar*), which also means 'precious stone' or 'jewel'.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] As the local people found it difficult to pronounce the Arabic word in the local dialect, the name subsequently became *Johor*.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Meanwhile, the Old Javanese eulogy of Nagarakretagama called the area *Ujong Medini* ('land's end'), as it is the southernmost point of mainland Asia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Another name, through Portuguese writer Manuel Godinho de Erédia, made reference to Marco Polo's sailing to *Ujong Tanah* (the end of the Malay Peninsula land) in 1292.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Both *Ujong Medini* and *Ujong Tanah* had been mentioned since before the foundation of the Sultanate of Malacca.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Throughout the period, several other names also co-existed such as *Galoh*, *Lenggiu* and *Wurawari*.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is also known by its Arabic honorific as دارالتّعظيم‎ (*Darul Ta'zim*) or 'Abode of Dignity'.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] A bronze bell estimated to be from 150 AD was found in Kampong Sungai Penchu near the Muar River.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Another important archaeological find was the ancient lost city of Kota Gelanggi, which was discovered by following trails described in an old Malay manuscript once owned by Stamford Raffles.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Artefacts gathered in the area have reinforced claims of early human settlement in the state.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Since ancient times, most of the coastal Malay Peninsula has had their own rulers, but all fell under the jurisdiction of Siam.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] After the fall of Malacca in 1511 to the Portuguese, the Johor Sultanate was established by Sultan Mahmud Shah of Malacca's son, Ala'udin Ri'ayat Shah II, in 1528 when he moved the royal court to the Johor River and set up his royal residence in Johor Lama.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor became an empire spanning the southern Malay Peninsula, Riau Archipelago (including Singapore), Anambas Islands, Tambelan Archipelago, Natuna Islands, a region around the Sambas River in south-western Borneo and Siak in Sumatra with Pahang, Aru and Champa as allies.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It aspired to retake Malacca from the Portuguese which the Aceh Sultanate in northern Sumatra also aspired to do leading to a three-way war among the rivals.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] During the wars, Johor's administrative capital moved several times based on military strategies and to maintain authority over trading in the region.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor and the Portuguese began to collaborate against Aceh, which they saw as a common enemy.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 1582 the Portuguese helped Johor thwart an attack by Aceh, but the arrangement ended when Johor attacked the Portuguese in 1587.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Aceh continued its attacks against the Portuguese, and only ceased when a large armada from the Portuguese port in Goa came to defend Malacca and destroy the sultanate.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] After Aceh was left weakened, the Dutch East India Company (VOC) arrived and Johor formed an alliance with them to eliminate the Portuguese in the 1641 capture of Malacca.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor regained authority over many of its former dependencies in Sumatra, such as Siak (1662) and Indragiri (1669), which had fallen to Aceh while Malacca was taken by the Dutch.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Malacca was placed under the direct control of Batavia in Java.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Although Malacca fell under Dutch authority, the Dutch did not establish any further trading posts in the Malay Peninsula and Sumatra, as they had more interest in Java and the Maluku Islands.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Dutch only become involved with local disputes when the Bugis began to threaten their maritime trade.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The dynasty that descended from the rulers of Malacca lasted until the death of Mahmud II, when it was succeeded by the Bendahara dynasty, a dynasty of ministers who had previously served in the Malacca Sultanate.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] This ended Bugis political domination in the Johor-Pahang-Riau empire, resulting in the Bugis being banned from Riau in 1784.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] During the rivalry between the Bugis and Dutch, Mahmud Shah III concluded a treaty of protection with the VOC on board the HNLMS *Utrecht* and the sultan was allowed to reside in Riau with Dutch protection.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Since then, mistrust between the Bugis and Malay escalated.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] From 1796 to 1801 and from 1807 to 1818, Malacca was placed under British Residency as the Netherlands were conquered by France in the Napoleonic Wars and was returned to the Dutch in 1818.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Malacca served as the staging area for the British Invasion of Java in 1811.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] When Mahmud Shah III died the sultan left two sons through commoner mothers.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] While the elder son Hussein Shah was supported by the Malay community, the younger son Abdul Rahman Muazzam Shah was supported by the Bugis community.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 1818, the Dutch recognised Abdul Rahman Muazzam Shah as the legitimate heir to the Johor Empire in return for supporting their intention to establish a trading post in Riau.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The following year, the British recognised Hussein Shah as the legitimate heir to the Johor Empire in return for supporting their intention to establish a trading post in Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Before his death, Mahmud Shah III had appointed Abdul Rahman as the Temenggong for Johor with recognition from the British as the Temenggong of Johor-Singapore, marking the beginning of the Temenggong dynasty.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Abdul Rahman was succeeded by his son, Daeng Ibrahim, although he was only recognised by the British 14 years later.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] As he maintained a close relationship with the British and the latter wanted full control over trade in Singapore, a treaty was signed between Daeng Ibrahim and Hussein Shah's successor, Ali Iskandar, recognising Ali as the next sultan.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Through the treaty, Ali was crowned as the sultan and received $5,000 (in Spanish dollars) and an allowance of $500 per month, but was required to cede the sovereignty of the territory of Johor (except Kesang of Muar, which would be the only territory under his control) to Daeng Ibrahim.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Following the establishment of a new capital in mainland Johor, the administrative centre was moved from Telok Blangah in Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] As the area was still an undeveloped jungle, the Temenggong encouraged the migration of Chinese and Javanese to clear the land and develop an agricultural economy in Johor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] During Daeng Ibrahim's reign, Johor began to be modernised which was continued by his son, Abu Bakar.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 1885, an Anglo-Johor Treaty was signed that formalised the close relations between the two, with the British given transit rights for trade through Johor's territory and responsibility for its foreign relations, as well as providing protection to the latter.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It was also in this year that Johor had formed its present-day boundary.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The treaty also provided for the appointment of a British agent in an advisory role, although no advisor was appointed until 1910.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Abu Bakar also implemented a constitution known as the Johor State Constitution (Malay: *Undang-undang Tubuh Negeri Johor*) and organised his administration in a British style.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] By adopting an English-style modernisation policy, Johor temporarily prevented itself from being directly controlled by the British, as happened to other Malay states.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Under the reign of Ibrahim, the British appointed Douglas Graham Campbell as an advisor to the sultanate in 1910, although the sultan only appointed Campbell as a General Adviser unlike in other Malayan states which had Resident Advisors, becoming the last Malay state to accept a British Adviser.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] However, due to Ibrahim's overspending, the sultanate faced problems caused by the falling price of its major source of revenue and problems between him and members of his state council, which gave the British an opportunity to intervene in Johor's internal affairs.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Despite Ibrahim's reluctance to appoint a British adviser, Johor was brought under British control as one of the Unfederated Malay States by 1914, with the position of its General Adviser elevated to that of a Resident in the Federated Malay States.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Since the 1910s, Japanese planters had been involved in numerous estates and in the mining of mineral resources in Johor as a result of the Anglo-Japanese Alliance.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] After the First World War, rubber cultivation in Malaya was largely controlled by Japanese companies.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Following the abolition of the *Rubber Lands Restrictions (Enactment)* in 1919, Gomu Nanyo Company (South Seas Rubber Co.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Ltd.) began cultivating rubber in the interior of Johor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] By the 1920s, Ibrahim had become a personal friend of Tokugawa Yoshichika, a member of the Tokugawa clan whose ancestors were military leaders (*shōgun* in Japanese) who ruled Japan from the 16th to the 19th centuries.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In the Second World War, at a great cost of lives in the Battle of Muar in Johor as part of the Malayan Campaign, Imperial Japanese Army (IJA) forces with their bicycle infantry and tanks advanced into Muar District (present-day Tangkak District) on 14 January 1942.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] During the Japanese forces' arrival, Tokugawa accompanied General Tomoyuki Yamashita's troops and was warmly received by Ibrahim when they reached Johor Bahru at the end of January 1942.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Yamashita and his officers stationed themselves at the Sultan's residence, Istana Bukit Serene, and the state secretariat building, Sultan Ibrahim Building, to plan for the invasion of Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Some of the Japanese officers were worried since the location of the palace left them exposed to the British, but Yamashita was confident that the British would not attack since Ibrahim was also a friend to the British, which proved to be correct.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] On 8 February, the Japanese began to bombard the northwestern coastline of Singapore, which was followed by the crossing of the IJA 5th and 18th Divisions with around 13,000 troops through the Straits of Johor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The following day, the Imperial Guard Division crossed into Kranji while the remaining Japanese Guard troops crossed through the repaired Johor–Singapore Causeway.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Following the occupation of all of Malaya and Singapore by the Japanese, Tokugawa proposed a reform plan by which the five kingdoms of Johor, Terengganu, Kelantan, Kedah-Penang and Perlis would be restored and federated.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Under the scheme, Johor would control Perak, Selangor, Negeri Sembilan and Malacca while a 2,100-square-kilometre (800 sq mi) area in the southern part of Johor would be incorporated into Singapore for defence purposes.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Meanwhile, Ōtani Kōzui of the Nishi Hongan-ji sub-sect of Jōdo Shinshū Buddhism suggested that the sultan system should be abolished and Japan should rule the Malay kingdoms under a Japanese constitutional monarchy government.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Japanese War Minister Hideki Tōjō, however, had already reminded their government staff in Malaya to refrain from acting superior to the sultan and to pay respect so the sultan would co-operate with the *gunsei* (Japanese military organisation).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In May, many high-ranking Japanese officials returned to Tokyo to consult with officials of the War Ministry and General Staff on how to deal with the Sultan.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Upon their return to Singapore in July, they published a document called "A Policy for the Treatment of the Sultan", which was a demand for the Sultan to surrender his power over his people and land to the Japanese emperor through the IJA commander.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The military organisation demanded the Sultan surrender his power in a manner reminiscent of the way the Tokugawa shogunate surrendered their power to the Japanese emperor in 1868.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Through the Japanese administration, many massacres of civilians occurred with an estimate that 25,000 ethnic Chinese civilians in Johor perished during the occupation.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In spite of that, the Japanese established the Endau Settlement (also known as the New Syonan Model Farm) in Endau for Chinese settlers to ease the food supply problem in Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] At the start of the war, the British had accepted an offer from the Communist Party of Malaya (CPM) to co-operate to fight the Japanese; to do this, the CPM formed the Malayan Peoples' Anti-Japanese Army (MPAJA).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The party also had Malay and Indian representatives.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] They advocated violence as a method of achieving their goals.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Throughout their war against the Japanese, they also assassinated civilians suspected of collaborating with the Japanese, while kidnapped Malay women were used as comfort women, as had also been done by the Japanese.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] This led to retaliatory raids from some Malays affected by the attacks who decided to collaborate with the Japanese.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] This indirectly led to ethnic conflict, especially when ethnic propaganda was being made by both sides, leading to the deaths of more civilians.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Allied forces launched Operation Tiderace and Operation Zipper to liberate Malaya and Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In the five weeks before the British resumed control over Malaya following the Japanese surrender on 16 August 1945, the MPAJA emerged as the de facto authority in the Malayan territory.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] There was a dispute after the British had returned when Lai Teck disappeared with the CPM funds.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The party administration was taken over by Chin Peng, who abandoned the "moderate strategy" in favour of a "people's revolutionary war", culminating in the Malayan Emergency of 1948.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] During the emergency period, large-scale attacks by the CPM occurred in the present-day Kulai District and other parts of Malaya, but failed to establish Mao Zedong-style "liberated areas".
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Fighting between the British occupation forces and their Malayan allies against the CPM continued through the formation of the Malayan Union on 1 April 1946 and the proclamation of the independence of the Federation of Malaya on 31 August 1957.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] At the time of independence there were three political factions: the Communists, the pro-British, and a race-based coalition.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 1961, the Prime Minister of the Federation of Malaya Tunku Abdul Rahman desired to unite Malaya with the British colonies of North Borneo, Sarawak and Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Despite growing opposition from the governments of Indonesia and the Philippines as well from Communist sympathisers and nationalists in Borneo, the federation was realised on 16 September 1963, with the sovereign state renamed Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Indonesian government later launched a "policy of confrontation" towards the new federation, which prompted the United Kingdom and their allies of Australia and New Zealand to deploy armed forces.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Pontian District became the coastal landing point for amphibious Indonesian troops during the confrontation while Labis and Tenang in Segamat District became the landing point for Indonesian para-commandos for subversion and sabotage attacks.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Several encounters occurred in Kota Tinggi District, where nine Malayan/Singaporean troops and half of the Indonesian infiltrators were killed and the rest were captured.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Despite several attacks that also cost civilian lives, the Indonesian side did not reach their main objective, and the confrontation ended in 1966 following the internal political struggle in Indonesia resulting from the 30 September Movement.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Since the end of the confrontation, the state's development has expanded further with industrial estates and new suburbs.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Of the total approved development projects for Johor from 1980 until 1990, 69 per cent were concentrated in Johor Bahru and the Pasir Gudang area.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Industrial estates and new suburbs were built in settlements on both the northern and eastern sides of the town, including Plentong and Tebrau.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The town of Johor Bahru was officially recognised as a city on 1 January 1994.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] On 22 November 2017, Iskandar Puteri was declared a city and assigned as the administrative centre of the state, located in Kota Iskandar.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is a constitutional monarchy and was the first state in Malaysia to adopt the system via the Johor State Constitution (Malay: *Undang-undang Tubuh Negeri Johor)* written by Sultan Abu Bakar in 1895.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The constitutional head of Johor is the sultan.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] This hereditary position can only be held by a member of the Johor royal family who is descended from Abu Bakar.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The current Sultan of Johor is Ibrahim Iskandar, who became sultan on 23 January 2010.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The main royal palace for the sultan is the Bukit Serene Palace, while the crown prince's is the Istana Pasir Pelangi; both palaces are located in the state capital.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Other palaces are the Grand Palace (which is also located in the state capital), Tanjong Palace in Muar, Sri Lambak in Kluang and Shooting Box in Segamat.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor was a sovereign state from 1948 until 1957 while the Federation of Malaya Agreement was in force, but its defence and external affairs were mainly under the control of the United Kingdom.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Malayan Federation was then merged with two British colonies in Borneo – North Borneo and Sarawak – to form the Federation of Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Other social issues include the rise of racial and religious intolerance among the state's citizens since being part of the federation.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state government is headed by a Chief Minister, who is assisted by an 11-member executive council selected from the state assembly members.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The legislative branch of Johor's government is the Johor State Legislative Assembly, which is based on the Westminster system.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Therefore, the chief minister is appointed based on their ability to command the majority of the state assembly.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state assembly makes laws in matters regarding the state.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Members of the Assembly are elected by citizens every five years by universal suffrage.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The majority (40 seats) are currently held by Barisan Nasional (BN).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is divided into ten districts (*daerah*), 103 mukims and 16 local governments.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] There are district officers for each district and a village head person (known as a *ketua kampung* or *penghulu*) for each village in the district.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Before the British arrival, Johor was run by a group of relatives and friends of the sultan.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] A more organised administration was developed in the treaty of friendship with Great Britain in 1885.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] A British Resident began to be accepted in 1914 when the state became part of the Unfederated Malay States (UMS).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] With the transformation into British-style administration, more Europeans were appointed into the administration with their role expanding from advising on financial matters to modern administration guidance.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Malay state commissioners worked alongside British district officers, known in Johor as "Assistant Advisers".
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] When the post of the Resident of the UMS was abolished, other European-held posts in the administration were replaced with locals.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] As in the rest of Malaysia, the local government comes under the purview of the state government.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Ninth Schedule of the Constitution of Malaysia states that the Malaysian federal government is solely responsible for foreign policy and military forces in the country.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] However, Johor has a private army, the only state to do so.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The retention of the army was one of the stipulations Johor made in 1946 when it participated in the Federation of Malaya.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] This army, the Royal Johor Military Force (*Askar Timbalan Setia Negeri Johor*), has served as the protector of the Johor monarchs since 1886.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It is one of the oldest military units in present-day Malaysia and had a significant historical role in the suppression of the 1915 Singapore Mutiny and served in both World Wars.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor previously had a territorial dispute with Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 1979 Government of Malaysia published the Malaysian Territorial Waters and Continental Shelf Boundaries Map which showed the island of Batu Puteh (present-day Pedra Branca) as under their jurisdiction, Singapore lodged a formal protest the following year.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The dispute originally concerned only the one feature, but when both sides agreed to refer the matter to the International Court of Justice (ICJ) in 2003, the dispute was enlarged to include two other features in the vicinity, Middle Rocks and South Ledge.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2008 the ICJ decided that "Batu Puteh belongs to Singapore, Middle Rocks to Malaysia and South Ledge belongs to the state in the territorial waters of which it is located".
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2017, Malaysia appealed the case of Pedra Branca based on the conditions required by the ICJ that a case could be revised within six months of discovery of facts and within ten years of the date of judgement following the discovery of several facts.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The request was dropped following internal changes in the new Malaysian administration the following year where they subsequently acknowledged Singapore's permanent sovereignty over the island while announcing plans to convert the Middle Rocks into an island.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The total land area of Johor is nearly 19,166 square kilometres (7,400 sq mi), and it is surrounded by the South China Sea to the east, the Straits of Johor to the south and the Straits of Malacca to the west.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The southernmost point of mainland Eurasia, is located at Tanjung Piai.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state has 400 kilometres (250 mi) of coastline, of which 237.7 kilometres (147.7 mi) have been eroding.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] A majority of its coastline, especially on the west coast is covered with mangrove and nipah forests.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The east coast is dominated by sand beaches and rocky headlands, while the south coast consists of a series of alternating headlands and bays.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Its exclusive economic zone extends much further in the South China Sea than in the Straits of Malacca.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The western part of Johor had a considerable amount of peatland.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2005, the state recorded 391,499,002 hectares (967,415,102 acres) of forested land, which is classified into natural inland forest, peat swamp forest, mangrove forest and mud flat.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] About 83% of Johor's terrain is lowlands, while only 17% is higher and steep terrain.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] While being relatively flat, Johor is dotted with many isolated peaks known as inselbergs, including isolated massifs.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Mount Ledang, also known as Mount Ophir, in the district of Tangkak and near the tripoint with Malacca and Negeri Sembilan, is the state's highest point at 1,276 metres above sea level.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Also in the state are Mount Besar, Mount Belumut and Mount Panti, which form the southern foothills of the Tenasserim Hills that extends from southern Myanmar and Thailand.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Since the state also lies on the Sunda Plate, it experiences tremors from nearby earthquakes in Sumatra, Indonesia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Much of central Johor is covered with dense forest, where an extensive network of rivers originating from mountains and hills in the area spreads to the west, east and south.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] On the west coast, the Batu Pahat River, Muar River and Pontian River flow to the Straits of Malacca, while the Johor River, Perepat River, Pulai River, Skudai River and Tebrau River flow to the Straits of Johor in the south.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Endau River, Mersing River, Sedili Besar River and Sedili Kecil River flow to the South China Sea in the east.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Johor River Basin covers an area of 2,690 kilometres, starting from Mount Belumut (east of Kluang) and Mount Gemuruh (to the north) downstream to Tanjung Belungkor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The river originates from the Layang-Layang, Linggiu, and Sayong rivers before converging into the main river and flowing southeast to the Straits of Johor for 122.7 kilometres (76.2 miles).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Its tributaries include the Berangan River, Lebak River, Lebam River, Panti River, Pengeli River, Permandi River, Seluyut River, Semangar River, Telor River, Tembioh River, and Tiram River.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Other river basins in Johor including the Ayer Baloi River, Benut River, Botak Drainage, Jemaluang River, Pontian Besar River, Sanglang River, Santi River, and Sarang Buaya River.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is located in a tropical region with an equatorial climate.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Both the temperature and humidity are consistently high throughout the year with heavy rainfall.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Average monthly temperatures between 26 °C (79 °F) and 28 °C (82 °F), with the lowest recorded during the rainy seasons.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The west coast receives an average of between 2,000 millimetres and 2,500 millimetres of rain, while in the east the average rainfall is higher, with Endau and Pengerang receiving more than 3,400 millimetres of rain a year.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state experiences two monsoon seasons, the northeast and southwest seasons; the northeast occurs from November until March while the southeast occurs from May until September, and the transitional months for the monsoon seasons are April and November.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state experienced extreme flooding from December 2006 to January 2007 with around 60,000–70,000 of the state residents evacuated to an emergency shelter.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The jungles of Johor host a diverse array of plant and animal species, with an estimated 950 vertebrates species, comprising 200 mammals, 600 birds and 150 reptiles, along with 2,080 invertebrate species.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Endau-Rompin National Park is the largest national park in the state, covering an area of 48,905 hectares (120,847 acres) in northern Johor; its name comes from the Endau and Rompin rivers that flow through the park.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Destinations in Peta including the Buaya Sangkut Waterfalls, Upeh Guling Waterfalls, Air Biru Lake, Janing Barat, Nature Education and Research Centre (NERC), Kuala Jasin and Peta indigenous village, while in Selai the area is mostly for hiking and jungle trekking.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Some mammal species found in the park include the Asian elephant, clouded leopard, Malayan sun bear, Malayan tapir and Malayan tiger.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Gunung Ledang National Park in western Johor, was established in 2005 with an area of 8,611 hectares (21,278 acres).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It has various rivers and streams, waterfalls, diverse rainforest, pines, and sub-montane forest, and the Tangkak Dam can also be seen from the park area.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Several trails for hiking are available, such as the Asahan Trail, Ayer Panas Trail, Jementah Trail and Lagenda Trail.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state's only marine park, the Sultan Iskandar Park, is located off the east coast and is made up of 13 islands in six clusters, Aur, Besar, Pemanggil, Rawa, Sibu and Tinggi, with an area of more than 8,000 hectares (19,768 acres).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2003, three wetlands in southern Johor comprising Kukup Island, Pulai River and Tanjung Piai were designated as a Ramsar site.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Tanjung Piai covers an area of 526 hectares (1,300 acres) of mangroves and another 400 hectares (988 acres) of inter-tidal mudflats, Pulai River with 9,126.0 hectares (22,551 acres) and Kukup Island with 647 hectares (1,599 acres) surrounded by some 800 hectares (1,977 acres) of mudflats.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The Pulai River became a seahorse sanctuary and hatchery as part of the state biodiversity masterplan, since Johor's waters are home to three of the eight seahorse species found in Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Poaching is a concern, with the number of wild animals in state parks decreasing with the rise of hunting and fishing in the 2000s.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2004, local authorities uncovered large-scale sandalwood (*gaharu*) poaching by foreigners in the Endau-Rompin National Park with a large number of protected plant species being confiscated from the suspects.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The conversion of mangrove areas along the southern and eastern coasts for use in aquaculture projects, sand mining and rapid urbanisation in addition to the abnormal weather patterns caused by climate change and rising sea levels are contributing to the erosion of the state's coastline.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It has also been discovered that some 68,468 hectares (169,188 acres) of peatland soils in western Johor have been planted with palm oil plantations.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2017, around 28 rivers in the state were categorised as polluted, leading the authorities and government to push for legislative change and sterner action against river polluters, especially since severe pollution has disrupted the water supply to an estimated 1.8 million people in the state.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The 2019 Kim Kim River toxic pollution affected 6,000 residents of the industrial area of Pasir Gudang with 2,775 being hospitalised.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Forest fires have also become a concern with more than 380 recorded throughout the state in 2016.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor's economy is mainly based on the tertiary sector, namely services, manufacturing, construction, etc.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2023, the gross domestic product (GDP) of Johor was RM148.2 billion, the second highest among Malaysian states after Selangor and the largest outside the Klang Valley.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state's median income was RM5,652 in 2024, making it the state with the second highest median household income.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2024, Johor had the fastest GDP growth rate among all Malaysian states and accounted for 9.6 per cent of Malaysia's GDP.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state has the largest services sector and real estate development outside the Klang Valley, with the former contributing 8.6 percent of the country's services sector's GDP in 2023.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is the top investment destination in Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It has been ranked the top state in Malaysia for six consecutive years in approved manufacturing projects valued at RM145 billion from 2013 to 2018.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state attracted the highest foreign direct investment (FDI) among all Malaysian states in 2022, primarily in the manufacturing sector.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2017, RM16.8 billion came from domestic direct investment and RM5.1 billion came from foreign direct investment, with Australia, China and the United States being the top three foreign investors in manufacturing.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] With the influx of foreign investments, Johor has also been ranked the second largest artificial intelligence hub globally.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is the second largest trade contributor in Malaysia, and has the second largest share of the country's imports, after Selangor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state is also Southeast Asia's largest data centre hub and the third largest in Asia Pacific.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] As a prominent regional manufacturing hub, the state is home to major multinational corporations (MNCs) in Malaysia, like ByteDance, Nvidia, Microsoft, Micron, Saudi Aramco, Foxconn, among others.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Its capital city, Johor Bahru, has been ranked the world's 20th most attractive city for businesses, second in Malaysia after Kuala Lumpur, according to Oliver Wyman, a New York-based management consulting firm.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Iskandar Malaysia located in southern Johor, is the largest special economic zone in Malaysia by investment value and GDP per capita, encompassing the city centre of Johor Bahru, Iskandar Puteri, Kulai District, Pasir Gudang and South Pontian.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It is a major development zone in the nation with an area of 221,634 hectares (2,216.34 km2).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] It primarily focuses on trading and services, manufacturing, business and finance, logistics, artificial intelligence, modern farming and ecotourism.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] With the establishment of the Johor-Singapore Special Economic Zone, the state is set to rival Klang Valley, the main economic region in Malaysia, in the next decade.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The total industrial area in the state as of 2015 was 144 km2 (56 sq mi) or 0.75 per cent of the land in Johor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state also houses Johor Corporation, a state-owned conglomerate involved in various business activities in the state and overseas.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is also the largest agriculture output contributor in Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The main agricultural sectors in the state are palm oil plantations, rubber plantations, and produce.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2015, land area used for agriculture in Johor covered 11,555 km2 (4,461 sq mi), 60.15 per cent of the state, with other plantations including herbs and spices.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 2016, palm oil plantations covered 7,456 km2 (2,879 sq mi) (38.8 per cent of the total land area), making it the third largest plantation area in Malaysia after Sabah and Sarawak.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Farmers' markets (Malay: *pasar peladang*) are used to distribute the agricultural produces which are located around the state.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor is the biggest fruit producer in Malaysia, with a total fruit plantation area of 414 km2 (160 sq mi) and total harvesting area of 305 km2 (118 sq mi).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In the same year, Johor was the second biggest producer of vegetables among Malaysian states after Pahang, with a total vegetable plantation area of 154 km2 (59 sq mi) and a total harvesting area of 143 km2 (55 sq mi).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Kluang District also had the largest vegetable plantation and harvesting areas, with a total area of 36 km2 (14 sq mi), and the highest total vegetable production at 60,102 tons.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] Johor benefits from Singaporean investors and tourists due to its close proximity to Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] From 1990 to 1992, approved Singaporean investments in Johor amounted to about US$500 million in 272 projects.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] In 1994, the investment from Singapore was nearly 40% of the state's total foreign investment.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The state also had a policy of "twinning with Singapore" to promote their industrial development, which increased the movement of people and goods between the two.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p01] The close economic links between the two began with the establishment of the Indonesia–Malaysia–Singapore Growth Triangle (SIJORI Growth Triangle) in 1989.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Johor Department of Economy Planning is responsible for all public infrastructure planning and development in the state, while the Landscape Department is responsible for the state's landscape development.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Since the Ninth Malaysia Plan, the Johor Southern Corridor has been a focus for development.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2010, the total state land used for commercial buildings was 21.53 km2 (8.31 sq mi), with Johor Bahru District accounting for 12.99 km2 (5.02 sq mi) or 63.5%.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Since 2012, around RM2.63 billion has been allocated by the federal and state governments for 33 infrastructure projects in Pengerang in southeastern Johor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The 2015 state budget included spending more than RM500 million for development in the following year – the highest amount ever allocated.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state government also ensured that infrastructure and development projects would be fairly distributed to all districts in the state, with six focus areas outlined in the state government's strategic development plan in 2018.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In the same year, the federal government allocated RM250 million for three infrastructure projects to improve connectivity and accessibility within the state capital.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Electricity distribution in the state is managed by Tenaga Nasional Berhad.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Most electricity is generated by coal and gas-fired plants.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The coal power plant had a capacity of 700 MW in 2007 and 3,100 MW in 2016, which originated from the Tanjung Bin Power Station in Pontian.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Two gas-fired plants, Pasir Gudang Power Station with 210 MW and Sultan Iskandar Power Station with 269 MW, are located in Pasir Gudang.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Pasir Gudang Power Station was retired from the system in 2016.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state government has been planning to construct hydropower and combined cycle power plants since 2015 and 2018 respectively.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] A new combined cycle power plant was constructed on a greenfield site near the old decommissioned power plants in Pasir Gudang, named the Sultan Ibrahim Power Plant.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] All water supply pipes in the state are managed by the Water Regulatory Bodies of Johor, with a total of 11 reservoirs: Congok, Gunung Ledang, Gunung Pulai 1, Gunung Pulai 2, Gunung Pulai 3, Juaseh, Layang Lower, Layang Upper, Lebam, Linggiu and Pontian Kechil.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state also supplies raw water to Singapore for RM0.03 for every 3.8 cubic metres (1,000 US gal) drawn from Johor rivers.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In return, the Johor state government pays the Singaporean government 50 cents (RM0.50) for every 3.8 cubic metres of treated water from Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] As of August 2022, Johor had the largest 5G internet coverage in Malaysia, Johor Bahru's internet speed is also the fastest in Malaysia and second in Southeast Asia, after Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Telecommunications in Johor were originally administered by the Posts and Telecommunication Department and maintained by the British Cable & Wireless Communications, which was responsible for all telecommunication services in Malaya.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] During this time, a troposcatter system was installed on Mount Pulai in Johor and Mount Serapi in Sarawak to connect radio signals between British Malaya and British Borneo, the only such system for both territories to allow simultaneous transmission of radio programs to North Borneo and Sarawak.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 1968, following the foundation of the Federation of Malaysia, the telecommunication departments in Malaya and Borneo merged to form the Telecommunications Department Malaysia, which later became Telekom Malaysia (TM).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Early in 1964, Ericsson –a Nordic telecommunication company– began operating in the country.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Following the first AXE telephone exchange in Southeast Asia that went online in Pelangi in 1980, TM was provided with the first mobile telephone network, named ATUR, in 1984.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Since then, the Malaysia's cellular network has expanded rapidly.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] From 2013 until 2017, the state mobile-cellular penetration rate has reached 100%, with 11.3% to 11.5% of the population using the internet.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2018, the state internet speed was 10 Mbps with the government urging the Malaysian Communications and Multimedia Commission to develop high-speed Internet infrastructure to reach 100 Mbit/s to match the state's current rapid development.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Malaysian federal government operates one radio channel – Johor FM through its Department of Broadcasting, officially known as Radio Televisyen Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There is one independent radio station, Best FM, which launched in 1988.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Television broadcasting in the state is divided into terrestrial and satellite television.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There are two types of free-to-air television providers, MYTV Broadcasting (digital terrestrial) and Astro NJOI (satellite), while IPTV is accessed via Unifi TV through the UniFi fibre optic internet subscription.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state is linked to the other Malaysian states and federal territories on the western coast through the North–South Expressway and on the eastern coast through Malaysia Federal Route 3.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Since British colonial times, there has been a road system linking Johor's capital in the southern Malay Peninsula to Kangar in the north and Kota Bharu on the east coast.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The roads in Johor are classified into two categories; 2,369 kilometres (1,472 mi) are federal roads while 19,329 kilometres (12,010 mi) are state roads, as of 2016.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor uses a dual carriageway with the left-hand traffic rule, and towns in the state provide public transportation services such as buses and taxis along with Grab services.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Sungai Johor Bridge is in Johor, which is the longest central span river-crossing bridge in Malaysia and connects Johor Bahru and Kota Tinggi District.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There are various expressways in the state capital city, including Tebrau Highway, Johor Bahru Eastern Dispersal Link Expressway, Pasir Gudang Highway, and others.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2018, construction of the Iskandar Malaysia Bus Rapid Transit was announced to be completed before 2021.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The previous federal government had allocated RM29.43 billion as part of the Eleventh Malaysia Plan for infrastructure projects including upgrading roads and bridges.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state government also spends over RM600 million on road maintenance annually.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Rail transport in the state is operated by Keretapi Tanah Melayu (KTM).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The railway line is connected to all of the states in western Peninsular Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] It is also connected to stations in Singapore and Thailand.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The KTM ETS service was extended into Johor in 2025, beginning with Segamat railway station in March, towards Kluang railway station in August and Johor Bahru Sentral station in December.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] With its full completion, travel time by rail between Kuala Lumpur Sentral station and Johor Bahru Sentral station was reduced to 3.5 hours.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The upcoming Johor Bahru–Singapore Rapid Transit System (RTS Link) linking Johor Bahru to Woodlands, Singapore will be the first rapid transit system outside the Klang Valley.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Senai International Airport is the largest and the only international airport in Johor, which acts as the main gateway to the state.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The airport is located in Senai Town, Kulai District.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2016, the Malaysian federal government approved a total of RM7 million in upgrades for the airport.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Four airlines fly to Johor: AirAsia, Malaysia Airlines, Firefly and Batik Air Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Other minor airports including Kluang Airport, Mersing Airport, Segamat Airstrip and Batu Pahat Airstrip in Kluang District, Mersing District, Segamat District and Batu Pahat District, respectively.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor has four ports in Iskandar Puteri and Pasir Gudang, which operate under three different companies.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Port of Tanjung Pelepas in western Iskandar Malaysia is currently the 15th busiest port in the world, and the largest transshipment hub in Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor also has two other container ports, the Integrated Container Terminal in Tanjung Langsat and Johor Port in Pasir Gudang.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Tanjung Langsat Terminal serves as the state's regional oil and gas hub and supports offshore petroleum exploration and production, while Johor Port is the world's largest palm oil terminal.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There are boat services to ports in Batam and Tanjung Pinang of the Bintan Islands in Indonesia and to port in Changi in Singapore.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Health-related matters in Johor are administered by the Johor State Health Office (Malay: *Jabatan Kesihatan Negeri Johor*).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2009, the state's doctor–patient ratio was 3 per 1,000 population.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] All primary and secondary schools are under the jurisdiction of the Johor State Education Department, under the guidance of the national Ministry of Education.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The oldest school in Johor is the English College Johore Bahru (1914).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor has a considerable number of Malay and indigenous students enrolled in Chinese schools.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There is also an Indonesian school in the state capital mainly for the children of Indonesian migrants.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There are two Japanese learning centres in Johor Bahru.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state government also emphasises pre-school education in the state with the establishment of several kindergartens such as Nuri Kindergarten and Childcare, Stellar Preschool and Tadika Kastil.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor has three public universities, the University of Technology Malaysia (UTM) in Skudai, Tun Hussein Onn University of Malaysia in Parit Raja, and Universiti Teknologi MARA Johor in Jementah and the state capital.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] As of 2024, UTM is the second highest ranked university in Malaysia, after University of Malaya, according to Webometrics Ranking of World Universities.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] EduHub Pagoh, the largest public higher education hub in Malaysia, is being constructed at Bandar Universiti Pagoh, a new planned education township in Muar.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state also houses a number of international university branches, including Newcastle University Medicine Malaysia, Netherlands Maritime Institute of Technology, University of Southampton Malaysia, University of Reading Malaysia, Monash University Malaysia Clinical School, and others.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There are several polytechnics including Ibrahim Sultan Polytechnic and Mersing Polytechnic; and two teaching colleges, IPG Kampus Temenggong Ibrahim in Johor Bahru and IPG Kampus Tun Hussien Onn in Batu Pahat.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] It has one non-profit community college, Southern University College in Skudai.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There is also a proposal to establish the University of Johor that has been welcomed by the Sultan of Johor with the federal education ministry also willing to extend their co-operation.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] To ensure the quality of education in the state, the state government introduced six long-term measures to upgrade the capability of local teachers.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2018, it was reported that Johor was among several Malaysian states facing a teacher shortage, so the federal education ministry set up a special committee to study ways to tackle the problem.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Johor State Library is the main public library in the state.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The 2023 Malaysian census reported the population of Johor at 4,100,900, with a non-citizen population of 276,900, making it the second most populous state in Malaysia, after Selangor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Despite the racial diversity of the population, most people in Johor identify themselves as "*Bangsa Johor*" (English: *Johor race*), which is also echoed by Johor's royal family to unite the population regardless of ancestry.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor Bahru District, anchoring the state capital Johor Bahru, is currently the second most populous district in Malaysia with a population of 1.8 million, as of 2023.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] As Malaysia is one of the least densely populated countries in Asia, the state is particularly sparsely populated, with most people concentrated in the coastal urban areas, since towns and urban centres have massively expanded through recent developments.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] From 1991 to 2000, the state experienced a 2.39% average annual population growth, with Johor Bahru District being the highest at 4.59% growth and Segamat District being the lowest at 0.07%.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The total population increased by about 600,000 every decade following the increase of residential developments in the southern developmental region; if the pattern continues, Johor will have an estimated 5.6 million people in 2030, larger than the government projection of 4 million.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor is among the most popular destinations for expatriates in the region.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] As of 2018, nearly two thirds of foreign workers in Malaysia were located in Johor, Kuala Lumpur and Selangor, according to World Bank.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Due to its rapid development and diversified economy, Johor attracted the highest number of inter-state migrants among all Malaysian states, with an influx of over 11.9 thousand people in 2020, despite dropping in 2022.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Islam became the state religion upon the adoption of the 1895 Johor Constitution, although other religions can be freely practised.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] According to the 2020 Malaysian census the religious affiliation of Johor's population was 58.7% Muslim, 25.9% Buddhist, 8.2% Christian, 6% Hindu, 0.1% followers of other religions or unknown affiliations, 0.2% Taoist or Chinese folk religion adherents, and 0.2% non-religious.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The census indicated that 80.2% of the Chinese population in Johor identified as Buddhists, with significant minorities identifying as Christians (18.2%), Chinese folk religion adherents (1.6%) and Muslims (0.2%).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The majority of the Indian population identified as Hindus (73.5%), with significant minorities identifying as Christians (6.1%), Muslims (9.2%) and Buddhists (2.8%).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The non-Malay bumiputera community was predominantly Christians (68.3%), with significant minorities identifying as Muslims (21.6%) and Buddhists (15%).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Among the majority population, all Malay bumiputera identified as Muslims.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The majority of Johoreans are at least bilingual, with Malay as the official language in Johor.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Other multilingual speakers may also be fluent in English, Chinese and Tamil languages.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johorean Malay, also known as Johor-Riau Malay and originally spoken in Johor, Riau, Riau Islands, Malacca, Selangor and Singapore, has been adopted as the basis for both the Malaysian and Indonesian national languages.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Terengganu Malay, a distinct variant of Malay, is spoken in the district of Mersing near the border with Rompin, Pahang.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Different dialect groups of the Chinese language are spoken among the Chinese community in the state, including Hokkien, Teochew, Hakka, Cantonese, Hainanese, Foochow, and Henghua.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Indian community predominantly speaks Tamil.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There is also a significant number of Malayalee populations in parts of Segamat, Johor Bahru and Masai, who speak Malayalam as their mother tongue.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Moreover, small number of other Indian language speakers such as the Bengali, Telugu, and Punjabi language speakers are also present.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Many Malayalees and Telugus are often categorised as Tamils by the Tamils themselves, and by other groups, as they use the Tamil language as a *lingua franca* among other Indian communities as in other locations in Peninsular Malaysia.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2017, the Queen of Johor, as the royal patron of the Malaysian English Language Teaching Association, called for a more conducive environment for young Malaysians to master English since there has been a drastic decline in proficiency among the younger Malaysian generation.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor's culture has been influenced by different ethnicities throughout history, especially by the Arabs, Bugis and Javanese people, with the state also becoming a mixture of different cultures among the Chinese, Indian, Malay and aboriginal people.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] A strong Arab cultural influence is apparent in art performances like *zapin*, *masri* and *hamdolok* and in musical instruments like the *gambus*.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The *zapin* dance was introduced in the 14th century by Arab Muslim missionaries from Hadhramaut, Yemen, and was originally performed only by male dancers, although female dancers are now common.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The dance itself differs among five Johor regions, namely *zapin tenglu* and *zapin pulau* (Mersing), *zapin lenga* (Muar), *zapin pekajang* (Johor Bahru), *zapin koris* (Batu Pahat) and *zapin parit mustar* with *zapin seri bunian* (Pontian).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Another Arab legacy is the use of Arabic names with *wadi* (valley) for areas populated by the Arab community in the state capital such as "*wadi hana*" and "*wadi hassan*".
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Buginese and Javanese cultural influences are found in the *bosara* and *kuda kepang* dances introduced to Johor before the early 20th century by immigrants of respective communities.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The influence of Javanese language on the local Malay dialect is also noticeable from particular vocabulary collected in recorded observations.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] These cultural activities are normally performed at Malay weddings and religious festivals.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The aboriginal culture is also unique with a diversity of traditions still practised, such as the making of traditional weapons, medicines, handicrafts and souvenirs.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Chinese community holds the Chingay parade annually by the Johor Bahru Old Chinese Temple, which unites the five Chinese ethnic groups in Johor, namely Cantonese, Hainanese, Hakka, Hoklo and Teochew.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] This co-operation among different Chinese cultures under a voluntary organisation became a symbol of harmony among the different Chinese people that deepens their sense of heritage to preserve their cultural traditions.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Johor Bahru Chinese Heritage Museum describes the history of Chinese migration into Johor from the 14th to 19th centuries during the Ming and Qing dynasties.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The ruler of Johor encouraged the Chinese community to plant gambier and pepper in the interior.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Many of these farmers switched to pineapple cultivation in the 20th century, making Johor one of Malaysia's top fruit producers.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Cuisine in Johor has been influenced by Arab, Buginese, Javanese, Malay, Chinese and Indian cultures.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Notable dishes include nasi lemak, asam pedas, Nasi Beringin, cathay laksa, cheese murtabak, Johor laksa, kway teow kia, mee bandung, mee rebus, Muar satay, pineapple pajeri, Pontian wonton noodle, san lou fried bee hoon, otak-otak, telur pindang, and other mixed Malay dishes.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Popular desserts include burasak, kacang pool, lontong and snacks like banana cake, Kluang toasted buns and pisang goreng.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] International restaurants offering Western, Filipino, Indonesian, Japanese, Korean, Taiwanese, Thai and Vietnamese cuisines are found throughout the state, especially in Johor Bahru and Iskandar Puteri.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johoreans observe a number of holidays and festivals throughout the year including Independence Day, Malaysia Day celebrations and the Sultan of Johor's Birthday.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] As Johor has been part of Malaya since 1957, its athletes represented Malaya and later Malaysia at the Summer Olympic Games, Commonwealth Games, Asian Games and Southeast Asian Games.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The Johor State Youth and Sports Department was established in 1957 to raise the standard of sports in the state.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] There are four sports complexes in the state, and the federal government also provides aid to improve sports facilities.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] In 2018, as part of a federal government plan to turn Muar into Johor's sports hub, around RM15 million has been allocated to build and upgrade sports facilities in the town.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Located in Iskandar Puteri, the Sultan Ibrahim Stadium is the main stadium of the football club Johor Darul Ta'zim (JDT).
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] A dominant club in Malaysian club football since the 2010s, they have won the Malaysia Cup six times, the Malaysia FA Cup five times, the Malaysia Super League for twelve consecutive seasons between 2014 and 2026, and the AFC Cup in 2015.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] The state women's football team also won four titles in the Tun Sharifah Rodziah Cup in 1984, 1986, 1987 and 1989.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Another notable stadium in the state is Pasir Gudang Corporation Stadium in Pasir Gudang.
[src:ayam-kampong/johor-p02] Johor also launched its own esports league, becoming the second Malaysian state to introduce the sport to the Sukma Games, with the Johor Sports Council agreeing to include it in the 2020 edition.
